<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plays Unique Role in UN, Qin Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Ambassador Qin
Huasun said that China has always insisted on the purposes and
principles of the U.N. Charter, firmly opposed hegemonism and
power politics, safeguarded the interests of the developing
countries and made important contributions to maintaining world
peace and promoting development.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the 25th anniversary of China's resumption of its
legitimate seat in the United Nations, the Chinese permanent
representative to the U.N. told Xinhua that China is the founding
member of the United Nations and one of the five permanent members
of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of New China in 1949, the People's Republic
of China has been entitled to inherit the seat in the United
Nations. But, New China was excluded from the organization for 22
years due to the obstructions of some countries. Thanks to the
consistent efforts of the majority of developing countries, the
26th session of the U.N. General Assembly adopted resolution 2758
with an overwhelming majority of votes, resuming China's all
legitimate rights in the organization.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Qin said, China has always supported Asian, African
and Latin American peoples' struggle for national independence and
made efforts to the peaceful solution of major international and
regional issues.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of the Cold War, he said, China has played a
unique balancing role in accelerating multi-polarization and
safeguarding world peace.
</P>
<P>
Qin noted that in the past 25 years China has expanded and
deepened its cooperation and exchange with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
China has participated in U.N. activities in the political,
economic, disarmament, social, human rights, legal, scientific and
environmental protection fields. China has supported and attended
all the important international conferences sponsored by the U.N.
and organized the Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
While insisting on the principles of the U.N. Charter and norms
of international law, Qin said, China has showed flexibility in
dealing with specific issues in order to seek solutions acceptable
to all parties.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he said, the United Nations and its agencies
have become an important channel for China to import funds,
technology and information. The U.N. system has assisted a number
of projects in China in the energy, transport, agriculture,
education, public health, environment and disaster relief sectors.
On the other hand, in addition to its donations to the U.N.
agencies, China's efforts to eliminate poverty, increase
employment and realize social harmony are a contribution to the
U.N.'s endeavor to promote social development, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Taiwan's attempt to "return" to the U.N., Qin said that no
one of the 28 members of the General Committee voiced support for
Taiwan's "representation" in the organization when the agenda of
the 51st session of the U.N. General Assembly was discussed on
September 18. This was the fourth time the General Committee
resolutely rejected the item advocated by a very small number of
countries. The fact proves the firm stand of the overwhelming
majority of countries which are determined to maintain the
authority of the U.N. Charter and resolution 2758, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the prospect of the U.N. in the coming decades, Qin said
that the organization is confronted with both opportunities and
challenges as various forces will continue to cooperate and at the
same time compete in the organization at the turn of the century.
However, he said, the role of this most authoritative
intergovernmental organization cannot be replaced by any other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
With the development of China's modernization program, China
will play a greater role in the U.N. and further strengthen its
cooperation with the organization, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
