<HEADLINE> Duma Sets Up Budget Conciliatory Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia's State Duma, the lower house
of the parliament, set up a "conciliatory commission" Wednesday to
deal with the government's 1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
At its first hearing a week ago, the Duma rejected the 1997
draft budget proposed by the government, describing it as
unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
The commission, chaired by Duma speaker Gennady Seleznyov,
comprises "Our Home Is Russia" party leader Sergei Belyayev,
Liberal Democratic Party leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky, Communist
Party leader Gennady Zyuganov and Yabloko party leader Grigory
Yavlinsky and leaders of other political factions.
</P>
<P>
It also includes the heads of the major committees of the Duma.
</P>
<P>
The government planned to review the draft budget at its
meeting on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Alexander Livshits said, in response to
suggestions by lawmakers, that the government would make "certain
corrections" in the budget, including adding a separate provision
for financing military reform and increasing social and investment
spending.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that he would urge changes in the system of
taxation for individuals because a considerable portion of income
had been concealed from taxation.
</P>
<P>
Livshits also said he hoped the government and the Duma would
cooperate constructively and try to finalize the budget by the end
of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
