<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Renovate Technology for Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 23 (Xinhua) -- China is to renovate its power
generating facilities on a large scale to control pollution,
increase economic efficiency and guarantee the safe operation of
power grids, Lu Yanchang, vice-minister of power industry, said
today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national conference on power technology, Lu said
that by 2000, China should complete the technological renovation
of 7.5-8.0 million kilowatt medium- and low-pressure condenser
tube generating units, which have operated for at least 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The move aims to improve the capability of the units to meet
peak hour demands in power consumption, increase security, lower
consumption of energy, and improve environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a consumption reduction, Lu said in the coming
five years, the average coal use in power plants nationwide must
be reduced by 34 grams per kilowatt hour.
</P>
<P>
In addition, more than 95 percent of the voltage in major
cities across the country should meet the standard, and the
reliability rate of power supply must hit 99.9 percent at least,
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Lu said various power grids in China should strengthen
coordination in electricity supplies, so that the capability of
the country's five major regional power companies, and 15
provincial power companies, in the transfer and control of
electricity supplies could reach international advanced levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
