<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Queen Elizabeth Unveils Government Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Queen Elizabeth II opened this
morning the new session of parliament, the last one before the
general election, by outlining the British government policy, with
crime, education and health at the top of the program.
</P>
<P>
The government program announced by the queen at a traditional
parliamentary ceremony today included 13 bills.
</P>
<P>
She confirmed that there would be a bill to increase choice in
schools and improve discipline and standards, another aimed to
reform the sentencing of serious and persistent offenders and
moves to crack down on welfare fraud.
</P>
<P>
The government's plan to outlaw most handguns except low
caliber guns used in target shooting was also in the queen's
speech.
</P>
<P>
Other measures were to improve and develop primary health care
services, to strengthen powers to protect the coastline from
pollution from shipping and to support the fight against organized
crime, including the setting up of a National Crime Squad.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister John Major hailed the policy plans as a
"meaty" pre-election package, saying that the program showed the
government had not run out of ideas.
</P>
<P>
But Labor leader Tony Blair complained the program did little
to help the economy or long-term unemployed, and accused the
government of leaving the country in limbo, afraid to call an
election.
</P>
<P>
Liberal Democrat leader Paddy Ashdown said the Tories were
looking to win the election rather than helping the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
