<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 16:00 GMT, October 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Labor Party leader Thorbjoern Jagland will succeed
Gro Harlem Brundtland, the most influential figure in Norwegian
politics, on Friday as Norway's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The UN special envoy to Afghanistan, Norbert
Holl, on Wednesday failed to broker a ceasefire agreement among
Afghan warring factions, said a report reaching here.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Two police drivers were killed and five others
injured when a powerful car bomb exploded Wednesday at a hostel
in the heart of Srinagar, capital of India-held Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA - The leaders of the warring Iraqi Kurdish groups in
northern Iraq have agreed in principle to a ceasefire,
U.S. special envoy Robert Pelletreau told reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Senior Minister Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore has
been named the Architect of the New Century this year by the
American think-tank the Nixon Center for Peace and Freedom, the
Straits Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- Talks between New Zealand political parties
continued Wednesday in an effort to form a coalition government
after the October 12 general election failed to produce a
clear-majority winner.
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The spreading dengue fever disease in New Delhi,
capital of India, has claimed 251 lives with eight more deaths
reported in the past 24 hours in the city, hospital sources said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
SARAJEVO -- Municipal elections in Bosnia have been postponed
again until early next year, the Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) announced on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Defense Department is notifying 20,800
U.S. Gulf War veterans that they may have been exposed to nerve
gas during the destruction of an Iraqi chemical weapons depot in
1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
