<HEADLINE> Taliban Vow to Fight Till End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Afghan Taliban militia
today vowed to fight till the end to defend Kabul and other areas
of Afghanistan under their control while military threats are
mounting around Kabul, said reports from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
"We will defend the areas we have captured and where we have
implemented Shariat (Islamic law) until the last drop of our blood
and as long as one Talib (religious student) is still alive,"
acting Minister of Information and Culture Amir Khan Muttaqi was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, military chief of the former government Ahmad Shah
Masood issued orders to his frontline troops amassing north of
Kabul today in preparation for a major offensive against the
Taliban religious army.
</P>
<P>
"We have brought security and normality to Kabul and the
militia (ex-government) has been driven from the capital.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want insecurity to come back to the capital and we
promise to defend Kabul to the best of our ability," Muttaqi said.
</P>
<P>
Masood's combined force of several thousand moved into
positions near Mir Bacha Kot, about 20 kilometers north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Masood, who was pushed out of Kabul last month by the Taliban
troops, earlier said he wouldn't launch a direct attack on the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban warned that its forces would strike back at Rashid
Dostum, the northern Afghan warlord controlling seven provinces,
if his troops attacked the Taliban north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Muttaqi said if General Dostum attacked the Taliban alongside
the forces of the ousted government, the Taliban would have no
choice but to retaliate.
</P>
<P>
The warning came hours after a spokesman for the ex-regime said
Dostum's forces had joined Masood's troops in attacking the
Taliban north of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Masood and Dostum and another Afghan party have formed a
three-party opposition alliance against the Taliban after Masood
was driven out of Kabul.  
</P>
</TEXT>
