<HEADLINE> Zambia's Biggest Opposition Party to Boycott </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's biggest opposition
United National Independence Party (UNIP) today refused to take
part in the general elections scheduled for November 18 for what
it described as irregularities in the voters' registration.
</P>
<P>
UNIP President Kenneth Kaunda said the serious omissions and
errors in the voters roll have dis-enfranchised thousands of
eligible voters, adding the entire process has been characterized
by "irregularities which have caused lack of public confidence."
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, the former Zambian president, also accused the
government of "corruptly" choosing Nikuv, an Israeli company
which has conducted the voters registration exercise for the
elections, instead of more experienced companies.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda said the UNIP party officials would call upon all the
party members to boycott the presidential and parliamentary
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Top Leader Vows to Defend Kabul </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PESHAWAR, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Kabul will be defended at all
cost, top leader of the Taliban militia Mulla Mohammad Umar told
Afghan Islamic Press today in the southern Afghan city of
Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban leadership in Kabul made similar pledge today amid
mounting pressures on the Taliban around Kabul.
</P>
<P>
According to the Peshawar-based press, the 36-year-old
spiritual leader of the Taliban with one eye and a wooden leg said
education is a must for all men and women.
</P>
<P>
However, he said education for women would start after the
establishment of a central government in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that a Taliban government would be
recognized by the United Nations and other countries very soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Pakistani Interior Minister Nasirullah Babar
returned to Mazar-i-Sharif, stronghold of powerful northern Afghan
warlord Rashid Dostum, after Dostum refused to sign a ceasefire
agreement with the Taliban unless they leave Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Babar is expected to hold talks with Dostum, who earlier agreed
in principle to a ceasefire agreement brokered by Pakistan during
Babar's shuttle diplomacy last week.
</P>
<P>
UN special envoy to Afghanistan Nobort Holl also reached
Mazar-i-Sharif for a meeting with Dostum.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kabul said Ahmad Shah Masood, military commander
of the former government, has launched a big offensive with the
help of Dostum against the Taliban 20 kilometers north of Kabul
today.
</P>
<P>
Taliban spokesman Maulvi Abdul Ghafoor here claimed that the
offensive has been repulsed.
</P>
<P>
No independent confirmation is available so far.  
</P>
</TEXT>
