<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Protests Dalai Lama's Visit to European Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Tibet is an integral part of
China and no other nation, organization or individual should
interfere with the internal affairs of China, a spokesman for
the Chinese Mission to the European Union said here today.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made the remark here today in response to Dalai
Lama's ongoing visit to the European Parliament (EP) and the
European Commission (EC).
</P>
<P>
As an integral part of China, Tibet is now an autonomous region
under the Chinese sovereignty, he said, adding that no other
nation, parliament, organization or individual should interfere
with China's internal affairs in whatever way.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman pointed out that instead of being an ordinary
religious person, Dalai Lama was only a political exile who has
long been engaging abroad in activities aimed at splitting up
China.
</P>
<P>
Backed up by some foreign governments and organizations, Dalai
Lama has been intensifying his efforts abroad to split up China,
undermine its national solidarity and destabilize this autonomous
region of China, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
A number of EP members have lately invited the Chinese
political exile to visit and make speeches at the parliament and
some EP and EC leaders were even meeting him, which, according to
the spokesman, has constituted a serious violation of Chinese
sovereignty and rude interference with China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
China is paying close attention to developing its relations
with the EU, but such a relationship should be built on the basis
of mutual respect, mutual benefits, equality and non-interference
in each other's internal affairs, the spokesman believed.
</P>
<P>
It should be known that the Chinese government and its people
are always steadfast in their stand as far as their territorial
sovereignty and national dignity are concerned, and that they will
never give in to any outside pressure, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He finally asked the European Parliament and the European
Commission to take the interests of the whole into account to
avoid causing any undue harm to China-EU relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac to Issue Card of Honor to Ex-Fighters in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
will issue the Card of World War II Fighters to former French
members of the International Brigade which participated in the
Spanish Civil War of 1936-1939 engaging fascist forces.
</P>
<P>
The French government, which began to issue the card in 1993,
only has given it to the resistance fighters during World War II
and not the members of the International Brigade, because France
did not officially join the Spanish War.
</P>
<P>
Chirac expressed the will in a recent letter sent to Jean-Claude
Lefort, a member of the National Assembly from the Communist Party
and a member of the Association of the Friends of Fighters in
Republican Spain (ACER), according to the daily L'Humanite.
</P>
<P>
The president expressed his hope that "this measure could be
effective at the time of the transfer of the cinders of Andre
Malraux to the Pantheon on November 23."
</P>
<P>
Andre Malraux, a well-known French writer and resistance fighter
who joined the Spanish War, will have his cinders removed to the
Pantheon in the Latin Quarter of Paris, where are buried the cinders
of many great figures in French history.
</P>
<P>
Chirac said that the government has asked the Council of State,
which is the supreme jurisdiction body of France, to make the new
measure into a law, said L'Humanite.
</P>
<P>
A presidential decree on issuing the card, which will cover all
the former French members of the International Brigade still alive,
is being prepared by the Ministry of Former Resistance Fighters,
said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Some 130 former French members of the International Brigade, most
of them Communist Party members, are still alive today, while the
rest of the 8,500 Frenchmen and Frenchwomen who participated in the
Spanish War on the Republican side have died, according to the ACER.
</P>
<P>
However, many of the Communist fighters also joined the
Resistance War against Germany and therefore have already got the
card, said the association.
</P>
<P>
The International Brigade, manned by 35,000-50,000 volunteers
from 53 countries, combated the fascist forces of General Franco who
was supported by Italy and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
