<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Women Driven Into Prostitution in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- More foreign women in Greece
have been driven into prostitution in the last five years, said
local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
According to Grigoris Lazos, a researcher at the Athens
Panteion University, between 1991 and 1996 the number of foreign
women involved with prostitution in Greece increased by 387 percent
while that of Greek women dropped 22 percent. The ratio between
Greek and foreign prostitutes has also changed -- from 70 Greek to
30 foreign in 1991 to 40 to 60 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Prostitution is legal in Greece under certain conditions.
Prostitutes must have a license, be over 18 and work in licensed
brothels.
</P>
<P>
Lazos estimated there are about 10,500 women prostitutes in
Greece, including 6,100 foreigners. Most of the latter (53 percent)
come from Eastern Europe and 31 percent come from Central Europe
and the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The majority of foreign prostitutes work for an average 22
months in Greece and then go back to their country.
</P>
<P>
Another social activist and president of the Greek Human Rights
Foundation Aliki Yiotopoulou-Marangopoulou said prostitution had
become an organized crime, functioning under mafia rules. She
attributed much of the responsibility to the so-called civilized
and democratic Europe which had been turning its back on the
problem as long as victims remained within the third world.
</P>
<P>
She added the problem became more acute after the Soviet Union
broke up and Western Europe started being flooded by Eastern
European women in search of a way out from poverty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
