<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Beira Port Improves Handling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Beira Port in central
Mozambique is striving to improve its handling capacity as part
of the implementation of the "Beira Corridor" plan aimed at
boosting the regional trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed by David Gomes, the chief executive of the
Mozambican Port and Railway Transport Company.
</P>
<P>
The port had handled 530,000 tons of railway cargo by the end
of June, with its yearly capacity estimated to surpass 100 tons,
as compared with last year's 74 tons of goods.
</P>
<P>
The total handling capacity -- by land, sea and railways --
reached 420,000 tons last year and a higher figure is expected.
</P>
<P>
The "Beira Corridor" plan is funded by the European Union,
which has loaned the project 407 million ECUs in the past 10
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
