<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Appoints S. Africa's New Chief Justice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Johannesburg, October 23 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela today appointed Justice Ismail Mahomed as the
country's first post-apartheid Chief Justice to succeed Justice
Michael Corbett.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Cabinet Secretary Jakes Gerwel in
Cape Town after Wednesday's cabinet meeting. Corbett will retire
next year.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued in Cape Town, Mahomed, who is also
deputy president of the Constitutional Court, said it is vital
for the country's judiciary to restore the law's legitimacy in
the post-apartheid era.
</P>
<P>
Mahomed became South Africa's first black senior counsel in
1974 and was overlooked several times for the bench by the
former apartheid government.
</P>
<P>
He also served as a judge in neighbouring countries including
Swaziland and Lesotho, and later served as Chief Justice of
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
His 35-year practice at the bar included considerable civil
and criminal litigation although he concentrated on human rights
and appeared in numerous trials on behalf of some leading
anti-apartheid activists.
</P>
<P>
Mahomed was appointed as a permanent judge in South Africa in
1991.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Mahomed was appointed by Mandela to serve on the country's
first constitutional court.
</P>
<P>
And in 1996 he was appointed the Chairman of the South African
Law Commission, a statutory body which reviews and initiates
legislation in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
