<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda, Burundi Reject Zaire's Accusation of Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda and Burundi, two tiny
central African states neighboring their regional giant Zaire,
today categorically rejected an accusation by Zaire that their
troops have attacked the Zairean territory.
</P>
<P>
"The Zairean accusations are groundless," the Agence France
Presse (AFP) quoted Rwandan Foreign Minister Anastase Gasana as
saying at a press conference today in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
Burundian Foreign Minister Luc Rukingama also described the
Zairean accusation as "groundless," and he urged Zaire "not to
give up itself to passion and dramatization," AFP quoted Radio
Burundi as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France again urged the United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity to call an international conference
in the Great Lakes region in Africa to discuss the worsening
situation there.
</P>
<P>
Fightings have lasted for several months between Zairean troops
and the Banyamurenges, an ethnic Tutsi people who were originally
from Rwanda but have long settled in eastern Zaire, triggering the
exodus of some 230,000 Hutu refugees from their camps in eastern
Zaire's South Kivu province.
</P>
<P>
Zaire Tuesday for the first time accused the troops of Rwanda
and Burundi of invading North Kivu and South Kivu provinces, and
Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko, who is hospitalized in
Switzerland now, has ordered the government to take all means
necessary "to defend national territorial integrity."
</P>
<P>
Rwanda said today that although it is trying to exercise
restraint in the confrontation with Zaire, it will definitely
defend its territory if attacked.
</P>
<P>
"The (Rwandan) government is faced with the challenge of
reconstructing its country, and we don't have any intention of
engaging ourselves in conflict with the neighboring country," said
the Rwandan foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Zaire of supporting Hutu extremists who fled
Rwanda after inflicting a genocide against Tutsis and moderate
Hutus in 1994, in which at least half a million people were
killed.
</P>
<P>
"We were the victims of a genocide. There are fugitives (in
Zaire), and among them there are former military men of the
Rwandan Armed Forces (FAR), the Interahamwe militias, and the
politicians, who call for genocide," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister recalled that Zaire supported the FAR,
Hutu troops of the former government of Rwanda, in its war with
the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front from 1990 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
"It is no surprising that there is today complicity between
them," he said in reference to the alleged support given by the
Zairean government to Hutu extremists now taking refuge in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Claude Dusaidi, advisor of Rwandan Defense Minister Paul
Kagame, said that Zaire's accusation is only "an excuse for
continuing to exterminate its own citizens," the Banyamurenges.
</P>
<P>
"I imagine that the young Zairean Tutsis have decided to defend
themselves," he said, in reference to the Banyamurenges who are
regarded as Zairean citizens by Rwanda, but now called "rebels" by
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"Zaire is a problem for all the region," said Dusaidi, while
calling on the international community to stop thinking that "one
can do nothing about Zaire, because Zaire is like this." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
