<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Gives Funds for Voters' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has released
100 million Naira (about 1.25 million US Dollars) to the National
Electoral Commission of Nigeria (NECON) for the compilation of a fresh
voters's register.
</P>
<P>
But the sum is far from a propasal for 596 million Naira (about
7.45 million Dollars) NECON forwarded earlier to the presidency, the
News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency, the amount released would
not cover the cost of printing the voters' cards and their
registration forms which is estimated at 124 million Naira (about 1.55
million Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The production of authenic voters' register should have been
finished in the third quarter of this year, according to the
military government's transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
The work was delayed by the rainy season, which usually ends in
October, said NECON Chairman Chief Sunmer Dagogo-Jack last week during
the presentation of certificates of registration to the five political
parties whose establishment was announced at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the compilation of the voters' register might
not begin as planned if adequate funds were not made available on time
to NECON to enable it to take care of logistics and the erection of
sheds at the 110,700 voting centers in the country.  enditem

