<HEADLINE> 36 States to Attend African Women Conference in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 23 (Xinhua) -- 36 African countries
have confirmed participation in the second African women's
conference to be opened by President Benjamin Mkapa in Dar Es
Salaam tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference will focus on how to promote
solidarity among women leaders in Africa, Minister of Community
Development, Women and Children Affairs Mary Nagu told a press
conference at the international press center here today.
</P>
<P>
Nagu said the conference will be attended by 26 women
ministers, eight women deputy ministers and 43 members of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The first African women's conference was held in Ouagadougou,
Burkina Faso, in July last year.
</P>
<P>
Nagu said the conference, financed by the U.N. Population Fund
(UNFPA), will also be attended by representatives from the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
UNFPA Executive Director Dr. Nafis Sadik will also attend the
conference, she disclosed.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, participants will discuss how to
promote solidarity among women leaders in sub-Saharan African
countries through proposed regional or national networks and ways
to promote resources mobilization by training African women
policy makers.
</P>
<P>
The conference, to be organized into several training
workshops, is aimed at enhancing the capacity of African women
policy makers in moulding and utilizing public opinion in favor
of issues affecting women, adolescents and children.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian minister appealed to women in the country to
come up in big numbers to join the participants in a precession.
</P>
</TEXT>
