<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duma Claims Black Sea Fleet Russia's Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The State Duma, the lower house
of the Russian parliament, today adopted a bill, claiming the
Black Sea Fleet Russia's property and banning the division of the
fleet with Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The bill, passed on the eve of Russian President Yeltsin's
scheduled meeting with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma, would
prevent the Russian government from signing an agreement with
Ukraine dividing up the fleet.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers also instructed the Russian Foreign Ministry to
notify Ukraine of its decision.
</P>
<P>
The Black Sea Fleet, a major former Soviet fleet, is based on
the Ukrainian Peninsula of Crimea. Russia and Ukraine both claimed
it after the former Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Ukraine have reached a tentative agreement on
dividing the fleet, but there have been disputes over the status
of Sevastopol, the headquarters of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
Duma's bill banning the division of the fleet now goes to the
upper chamber, the Federation Council.
</P>
<P>
Some Duma deputies told reporters after the voting that if the
upper house approves the split-banning bill, it is sure to face
resistance from Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's envoy to the Duma told reporters at the same time
that "the bill should not have been passed without taking into
consideration the president's opinion."
</P>
<P>
An informed Kremlin source said that the Kremlin does not share
the optimism of the Ukrainian side which says the issue is
resolvable in the near future.
</P>
<P>
But Russia is going to continue the talks on the division and
basing of the fleet, the source said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
