<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Peace Process Not Easy: Major </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister John
Major warned the Irish Republican Army (IRA) today that "soft
words" alone would not earn its political allies a seat at the
talks table.
</P>
<P>
As the British parliament opened for its last session before
the country's general election, Major sounded pessimistic about
the chances of restoring momentum to a peace process that has been
stalled since the IRA resumed bombing British targets in February.
</P>
<P>
"I can not look into the minds of the terrorists and predict
what they will do. But I do know that the road to a settlement
will not be easy," Major said.
</P>
<P>
He said the IRA, by shattering its 17-month ceasefire, had
excluded itself and its political wing, Sinn Fein, from
multi-party talks that started in Belfest in June.
</P>
<P>
"But the talks will continue without them. The IRA and Sinn
Fein should be under no illusion that they can join the process
until they have demonstrated real commitment to democratic and
non-violent methods," Major said.
</P>
<P>
"So even if a new ceasefire is declared, there will have to be
more than soft words to convince the government," he added.
</P>
<P>
Major was speaking a day after a London police chief said
Britain faced "dangerous months" in which IRA guerrillas could
launch further attacks on the British mainland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
