<HEADLINE> SADC States Unhappy with Savimbi's Non-commitment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAMM, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Defense and Security
Ministers in Southern Africa are not happy with Angola's former
rebel movement UNITA's non-commitment toward the peace process in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Defense and National Service Maokola Majogo told
a press conference here today that the ministers from 12 SADC
countries who met in Lilongwe, Malawi last week, expressed regret
on the non-committal attitude displayed by UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi turned down an invitation to attend the special
Southern African Development Community (SADC) summit convened in
Luanda, Angola on October 2, which was aimed at strengthening the
peace process in the zone and in Angola in particular.
</P>
<P>
"The ministers strongly appealed to Dr. (Jonas) Savimbi to
honor the provisions of the Lusaka Protocol, and subsequent peace
agreements, without any further delay," Majogo said.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government and the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) signed the peace accord in Zambia
in 1994, pledging to end their 19-year civil war and realize
peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Savimbi refused to attend the summit held in Luanda, saying
he feared his security would be in danger if he attended the
meeting in the Angolan capital.
</P>
<P>
Member states to SADC include Mauritius, Angola, Mozambique,
South Africa, Malawi, Namibia, Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabweque,
Botswana, Swaziland, and Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzania delegation led by Defense Minister Majogo,
included minister for Home Affairs Ali Ameir Mohammed, Chief of
Defense Forces General Robert Mboma and Inspector General of
Police Omar Iddi Mahita. 
</P>
