<HEADLINE> Party Conventions Cost More Than Anticipated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- This summer's Republican
National Convention in San Diego cost both public and private
agencies about 45 million dollars, according to Federal Election
Commission financial statements.
</P>
<P>
The city of San Diego and its private host committee reported a
combined 31 million dollars in spending. Roughly three-fifths of
the total was funded by individual and corporate contributions.
</P>
<P>
The Port of San Diego and the San Diego Convention and Visitors
Bureau add some three million dollars to the total.
</P>
<P>
The rest was 12.2 million dollars the Republican National
Committee received from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
FEC statements released this week indicate San Diego's spending
was higher than originally announced by city officials.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Susan Golding initially estimated the city's convention
bid at a maximum 26 million dollars in public and private funds.
</P>
<P>
When the Republican National Committee later pegged the
host-city commitment at 31 million dollars, Golding said it was
"capped" at 23 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chicago had a similar experience with the 1996 Democratic
National Convention. It announced an initial bid of 32 million
dollars, later revised it downward to 28 million dollars and
finally reported host-city expenditures of 33.5 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
