<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Buying more U.S. Stocks This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investors are
flocking to U.S. Stocks this year as U.S. stock prices is going
up, The Wall Street Journal reported today.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners bought a net 6.9 billion dollars of U.S. stocks in
the second quarter of this year, the latest period for which data
are available, according to the Securities Industry Association, a
Wall Street trade group.
</P>
<P>
That was 87 percent more than they bought in the first three
months of this year and the highest amount since overseas
investors added 7.2 billion dollars of the U.S. stocks to their
portfolios in the first quarter of 1994, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In all, foreigners purchased a net 10.6 billion dollars in the
first half of this year, putting them on track to possibly match
the record 21.6 billion dollars they acquired in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Japanese investors bought a net 2.3 billion dollars of U.S.
stocks in the second quarter after dumping 789 million dollars in
the first three months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Europeans remain fickle. The largest buyers in the
second quarter were the Swiss, who purchased 556 million dollars.
But the French and Italians actually sold shares.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the steady climb of U.S. stock prices and a
strengthening dollar have produced an inviting environment for
foreign investors, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
