<HEADLINE> Worldwide Vigils to Protest U.N. Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Vigils will be held in
27 cities throughout the world this evening -- the eve of the
United Nations Day -- to protest the U.N.'s financial crisis and
to demand that all countries, especially the U.S., pay their U.N.
dues on time, in full and without condition, according to
organizers.
</P>
<P>
"Citizens are fed up with the hypocrisy of governments trashing
the United Nations and ignoring international law," William Pace,
Executive Director fo the World Federalist Movement, told
reporters here today.
</P>
<P>
"We are especially concerned at the refusal of the United
States, the host government, to pay its legally-obligated dues and
arrears," he added.
</P>
<P>
For over a year, the U.N. has been on the verge of financial
collapse. Member states now owe the organization 2.5 billion
dollars, and the U.S. alone owes 1.44 billion dollars, more than
all the other members combined.
</P>
<P>
The organizers, including World Federalist Movement, Global
Policy Forum and World Federation of the U.N. Association, noted
that the current U.S. share of the regular U.N. budget -- 321
million dollars -- is only 0.02 percent of federal spending or
less than one percent of New York City's annual outlays.
</P>
<P>
The cost of the total U.N. system, including peace-keeping,
health care, human rights, programs for children and women, food
and humanitarian relief, comes to less than 10 billion dollars per
year. By contrast, countries spent 36 billion dollars in 1994 on
the global arms trade and 850 billion dollars on military forces.
</P>
<P>
The organizers strongly criticize the U.S. which withholds the
payment to put pressure on the organization for its own political
purpose.
</P>
<P>
The vigils will be held in 13 U.S. cities such as New York
City, Boston, San Francisco, Philadelphia and Chicago and in 14
cities of Japan, Malaysia, Canada, France and other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
