<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Retail Sales Fall by 0.3 Percent in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- An unexpected 12.0 percent drop
in shoe sales contributed to a 0.3 percent fall in retail sales in
Britain last month, according to figures released Wednesday by the
Office for National Statistics (ONS).
</P>
<P>
The figures, compared with a 0.9 percent rise in August, helped
slow the rate of year-on-year sales growth to 3.5 percent from the
4.3 percent seen in the year to August.
</P>
<P>
City economists had expected a fall of 0.1 percent or so. But
the ONS said that the trend was positive, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
Prices of clothing and footwear rose sharply by 5.2 percent in
September and retail sales in this sector also fell sharply by 3.0
percent after jumping 2.2 percent in August, dragging down overall
retail activity in September.
</P>
<P>
However, the government welcomed the figures as evidence that
the consumer-led recovery is still well on track with little sign
of inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the figure will offer Chancellor of the
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke more support to resist Bank of England
governor Eddie George's call to raise interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
