<HEADLINE> U.S. Government OKs Direct Aid Flights to Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has
permitted American aid planes to fly directly to Cuba to deliver
food, clothing and medicine for Cuban victims of Hurricane Lili.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said today the
Treasury Department approved an application from the Catholic
Relief Services for an emergency flight to help large numbers of
Cubans left homeless by the hurricane last week.
</P>
<P>
The cargo plane could be headed to Cuba by the weekend, U.S.
Burns said. The flight is consistent with the U.S. policy of
people-to-people exchanges with Cuba, he added.
</P>
<P>
Direct flights to Cuba were halted in March, a month after
Cuban MiGs shot down two small planes belonging to a Miami-based
exile group.
</P>
<P>
According to a U.N. report, the hurricane destroyed 5,460 homes
and damaged 78,855 others. It also devastated more than 1.6
million acres of sugar cane plantations, 53,000 acres of banana
plantations and 90,000 acres of other crops. 
</P>
