<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Bidding War Breaks out for Rail Meager in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A bidding war broke out
today in a U.S. rail meager when Norfolk Southern Corp. announced
an offer for the Conrail which is nearly 1 billion dollars more
than CSX's offer last week.
</P>
<P>
Norfolk Southern is offering 8.1 billion dollars in cash for
the Conrail. The CSX cash and stock offer last week was initially
worth 8.4 billion dollars, but its stock price has fallen more
than 6 percent since then, pulling down the value of the total CSX
bid to a little under 7.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
Either merger would create one of the biggest railroad in the
U.S., a giant that would dominate the rail freight industry in the
East area in the country.
</P>
<P>
Norfolk Southern, which had been rumored earlier this year to
be interested in buying Conrail, had signaled its willingness to
disrupt the CSX deal when it was announced last week.
</P>
<P>
"A combined Norfolk Southern-Conrail will create a more
balanced eastern rail system and will do so by increasing, rather
than diminishing, competition in the industry," Norfolk Southern
chairman David R. Goode said in statement.
</P>
<P>
Goode said he had suggested a combination as recently as 11
days before the CSX deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
A combined Norfolk Southern and Conrail would, like a
CSX-Conrail deal, create the second largest railroad in the U.S..
</P>
<P>
A merged CSX and Conrail would serve the eastern half of the
United States from Chicago and New Orleans to Boston, New York and
Miami. CSX tracks are more evenly spread across the East than
Norfolk Southern's.
</P>
<P>
The bidding war for the meager of Conrail between CSX and
Norfolk Southern Corp. spotlights the harsh competition between
the U.S. rail transportation companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
