<HEADLINE> Pakistan Economic Growth Rate Reaches 6.1 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's economic growth
rate increased from 4.4 percent in 1994-95 to 6.1 percent in
1995-96 with the industrial sector growth rate standing at 6.1
percent, almost double that of the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
According to the Annual Report of State Bank of Pakistan issued
today, the growth rate of the three main sectors -- agriculture,
industry and services -- accelerated to a range of 5.8-6.7
percent, with the largest increase recorded in agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector registered a 6.7 percent increase in
1995-96, exceeding the target of 6.2 percent for the year and up
from the average growth rate of 5.6 percent in the preceding two
years and a negative growth rate of 5.3 percent in 1992-93.
</P>
<P>
Amongst the major crops, cotton production registered the
largest increase of 22.2 percent, indicating success in
controlling the leaf curl virus problem which had badly marred the
cotton performance in the preceding three years.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate, according to the Commercial Price Index,
decelerated from 13.0 percent in 1994-95 to 10.8 percent in
1995-96, although it was above the target of 9.5 percent, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The fall in the inflation rate was more pronounced in terms of
the wholesale price index, which decelerated from 15.0 percent to
10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Investment activities showed considerable buoyancy in
large-scale manufacturing and electricity and gas.
</P>
<P>
Real investment increased by 35.6 percent in large-scale
manufacturing and by 24.0 percent in electricity and gas in
1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of total investment to the gross national products
(GNP) increased from 18.6 percent in 1994-95 to 19.4 percent in
1995-96, with the large increase in private sector investment more
than offsetting the decline in the ratio of public sector
investment to the GNP.
</P>
<P>
The credit plan for 1995-96 was formulated to achieve the twin
objectives of controlling inflation and ensuring sufficient
availability of bank credits to meet the genuine financing needs
of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Net domestic assets increased by 20.2 percent, compared with an
increase of 12.3 percent in the previous year and the target of
14.3 percent for 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The major factor behind the excessive increase in net domestic
assets was government borrowings for budgetary support, which, at
53.6 billion rupees (1.34 billion US dollars), was well-above the
target of 28.1 billion rupees (703 million dollars) in the credit
plan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
