<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zaire to Complain About Rwanda, Burundi at U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Zaire will lodge a complaint
against Rwanda and Burundi at the United Nations Security Council
over what it alleges was "the attack" launched by the two
countries against its territory.
</P>
<P>
The National Radio of Zaire reported today that, on Wednesday,
a vice foreign minister of Zaire met with the ambassadors of the
five permanent member countries of the U.N. Security Council in
Kinshasa. The minister told them of the "the determination of
Zaire to lodge a formal complaint with supporting evidence."
</P>
<P>
It was certainly an attack by Rwanda and Burundi, and not an
interior rebellion as some wanted the people to believe, the vice
minister said.
</P>
<P>
"The Banyamurenges have always lived in peace with the local
population and their problem rises out of a question of
nationality, which will be solved by the law," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fighting has been going on for more than two months between
Zairean troops and the Banyamurenges, an ethnic Tutsi people who
were originally from Rwanda, but have long been settled in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda and Burundi Wednesday rejected the accusation by Zaire
that their troops attacked the South Kivu and North Kivu provinces
of Zaire, and said the accusation was only an excuse for
"terminating" the Banyamurenges.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government, which regards Banyamurenges as Zairean
nationals, said youths of the minority tribe were defending
themselves against government forces.
</P>
<P>
Zaire does not recognize the Banyamuranges, who number between
250,000 and 400,000, as its nationals. It has accused Rwanda of
providing arms and training to the "rebels."
</P>
<P>
At least 83 people, most of them local villagers, were killed
earlier this week in fighting between the Zairean troops and the
Banyamurenges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
