<HEADLINE> Iraqi Newspaper Accuses Foreign Powers of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi newspaper Al-Thawra,
mouthpiece of the ruling Baath party, today accused foreign
powers of interfering in the Kurdish affairs in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"These forces, chiefly the United States, bear the greater
part of the responsibility for the deterioration of situation in
northern Iraq," the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"The conflicting Kurdish factions should have the boldness to
restrain themselves, to reconsider their attitudes and to place
the interests of their homeland above maneuvers and narrow
interests..." the paper added.
</P>
<P>
It called on the rival Kurdish factions to enter into a
dialogue in order to put an end to their bloody conflict.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) have agreed in principle to a
cease-fire in northern Iraq, U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
Robert Pelletreau announced in Ankara Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Pelletreau made the announcement after concluding his talks
with Massoud Barzani, the leader of the KDP, and PUK's leader
Jalal Talabani.
</P>
<P>
He said that more talks will be held in Ankara next week in a
bid to end the clashes in northern Iraq between the KDP and PUK.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy, who arrived in Turkey Sunday, said that the
KDP and PUK agreed to attend the talks which will be held with
the participation of representatives from the U.S., Britain and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the KDP and PUK leaders would take part in the talks,
Pelletreau said: "I think they will send delegations, we will be
in an effort to lay the foundations of reconciliation agreement."
</P>
<P>
The latest clashes between the two rival factions erupted when
Barzani, aided by Baghdad's troops, took over northern Iraq in a
move which triggered U.S. military strikes on Iraqi missile
targets in early September.
</P>
<P>
Talabani retaliated two weeks ago and retook some of the lost
towns. 
</P>
