<HEADLINE> UNICEF Praises China's Contribution to Children's Welfare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior United Nations
Children's Fund official today praised China for its remarkable
achievements in child welfare.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Lewis, UNICEF executive director, recalled its
successful co-operation with China on the development of Chinese
children's welfare and education.
</P>
<P>
He said at a press conference that UNICEF has so far invested a
total of 220 million US dollars in a number of projects in China's
culture, education and public health.
</P>
<P>
"Many indicators used to determine the situation of Chinese
children have reached, or surpassed the requirements set forth in
the Manila Consensus, adopted by the 1993 Ministerial
Consultation, for the East Asia and Pacific Region.
</P>
<P>
He also praised China for providing 240 million Chinese
children - 80 percent of the total children in the country - with
regular medical tests, which has helped lower the rate of
vaccine-preventable diseases dramatically.
</P>
<P>
China's child population accounts for one-fifth of the world's
total.
</P>
<P>
Pratima Kate, UNICEF regional director for East Asia and the
Pacific, said that the mortality rate of infants in China was much
lower than 5.5 percent in the region, representing a decline of
14.5 percentage points from the figure 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Keshat Mathema, UNICEF representative to China said that the
UNICEF will conduct further cooperation in the fields of child
education and welfare in the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
