<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few Canadians Use Internet: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Despite all the fanfare about
Internet, few Canadians seem to have been lured into actually
surfing the information highway.
</P>
<P>
Currently, some 32 percent of Canadian households have a
personal computer, but only 7.4 percent of them actually use the
Internet from their home computers.
</P>
<P>
The figures are far lower than most Internet experts had
predicted, the Globe and Mail newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
In other words, 92.6 percent of Canadian households don't use
the Internet, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
Fewer than half of Canadian who had computers with modems were
hooked up, the paper quoted the latest Statistics Canada survey as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Quebec had the lowest usage of the Internet of any Canadian
province, with 4.1 percent of households hooked up, compared with
8.7 percent in neighboring Ontario, and about 10 percent in Albert
and British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
While lots of Canadians are buying computers, the machines are
often for their school-aged children, said Jim Carrol, holder of
the 1996 title Canadian Internet Person of the Year.
</P>
<P>
"To be honest, half of the people who have a modem don't know
what to do with it," he said, adding that Canadians remain largely
confused by computers in general, much less the intricacies of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
"The technology has outstripped the ability of people to deal
with it," he noted.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, hooking up to the Internet cost 15 to 23 U.S.
dollars a month, which may also help explain the fact fewer
Canadian are enthusiastic about the Internet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
