<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Day Celebrated in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Reasonable reforms of the
United Nations are necessary, but to enable the UN to maintain its
normal operation, all member states should meet their financial,
and other obligations under the Charter, Chinese Vice Foreign
Minister Li Zhaoxing said in Beijing today, at a meeting to mark
UN Day.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed that the reforms should give expression to the
principle of sovereign equality, and take such an approach of
democratic consultation, to fully reflect the aspirations and
demands of developing countries, which make up two-thirds of UN
membership.
</P>
<P>
October 24 was designated as UN Day by the second UN General
Assembly in 1947, and tomorrow will mark the 25th anniversary of
the restoration of legal rights of the People's Republic of China
in the UN.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 25 years, China discharged faithfully its duties
and obligations as a member state of the UN, and a permanent
member of its Security Council, Li pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has taken part in the work of the UN in
political, economic, disarmament, social, human right and legal
fields with a positive, pragmatic, earnest and responsible
attitude, adding China had become an active contributor to the
affairs of the UN through its effective work.
</P>
<P>
Li, on behalf of the Chinese government, expressed gratitude to
all those working in UN offices in China, who made praiseworthy
efforts over the years in promoting cooperation between the UN and
China.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of holding this function is to propagate the spirit
of the UN Charter, to let the 1.2 billion Chinese people have a
better understanding of the UN, and to support its activities and
cause of justice, said Xie Qimei, president of the UN Association
of China (UNA-China).
</P>
<P>
N. Holcombe, resident coordinator of UN operational activities
in China, pointed out that 1996 and 1997 will likely be critical
years for the UN, saying it needs the full support of member
states in clarifying and agreeing upon its future mandate,
structure and staffing.
</P>
<P>
On the difficulties in budget and other areas, Holcombe
said: "China regularly pays its dues to the UN, and is not one of
the 100 delinquents. The United States is the biggest delinquent,
owing over half the total, or 1.6 billion US dollars, for past and
current payments."
</P>
<P>
Among those attending the function, sponsored by UNA-China,
were representatives of the UN agencies in Beijing, diplomatic
envoys and diplomats to China, and scholars and specialists
engaged in UN studies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
