<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Price Index Goes Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Sensitive Price
Indicator (SPI) for the week ending October 21 showed an increase
of 0.33 percent over the index of the previous week.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released today by the Federal Bureau of
Statistics, the SPI, with 1990-91 as the base, stood at 190.65 for
the week ending October 21 against 190.02 for the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The SPI is higher by 11.98 percent as compared with the index
of the corresponding week of last year.
</P>
<P>
This upward movement is mainly due to rises in the prices of
wheat, flour, wheat, eggs, cooking oil and sugar.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Bureau of Statistics compiles the SPI every week,
with 1990-91 as the base, in respect of 46 essential commodities
mostly consumed by industrial, commercial and government employees
earning up to 1,500 rupees (37.5 US dollars) per month.
</P>
<P>
The price index of 19 daily food items for the week ending
October 21, 1996, rose by 0.65 percent from the previous week and
by 12.26 percent from the corresponding week of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
