<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Congratulates Arch-Foe on Election Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Thursday congratulated his arch-foe, Alexander Rutskoi, on being
elected governor of the Kursk region by a landslide.
</P>
<P>
In a greeting to Rutskoi, who was a former vice president,
Yeltsin said he hoped Rutskoi would "on this high post promote
stabilization of the social and economic situation in the region,
and further economic reforms aimed at improving the life of the
population."
</P>
<P>
The new post will give 49-year-old Rutskoi a place in the
Federal Council (upper house of the parliament) and a fresh role
in Moscow politics.
</P>
<P>
Rutskoi was Yeltsin's running mate when Yeltsin was first
elected in 1991. But they soon fell out, personally and
politically, and Rutskoi was jailed for leading the 1993 revolt
against the president.
</P>
<P>
Rutskoi and other mutiny leaders were arrested after a crack
down, but was freed later under the State Duma (lower house of the
parliament) amnesty.
</P>
<P>
Rutskoi, a decorated Afghan war veteran, went back into
politics after release by forming a nationalist movement called
Derzhava, or Great Power.
</P>
<P>
Failing to win enough support to enter the presidential
election race earlier this year, Rutskoi allied his party with the
opposition communists.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the alliance resulted in Rutskoi's
victory in Sunday's elections in the Kursk region, central
Russia. He gained 79 percent of votes, so staging a political
comeback despite the barriers in his way.
</P>
<P>
Rutskoi was initially barred from the regional elections, but a
"court decision" only 36 hours before the vote gave him a chance
to join the polls, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Yeltsin wished Rutskoi "success for the sake of
a flourishing of the Kursk region and the revival of Russia."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
