<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia "Definitely" Against NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia is definitely against the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization's eastwards expansion plans,
though it is ready to continue dialogue with it on strengthening
European security, a Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Tarasov, head of the ministry's information department,
said Russia was open to joint efforts to form a basis for its
relations with NATO in a bid to set up a European security system
involving all European nations.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a recent statement by United States President
Bill Clinton on admitting some Central and Eastern European
nations into NATO, Tarasov said Russia was "definitely against
NATO's expansion," but would not "turn its back on (maintaining)
contact with NATO."
</P>
<P>
He said NATO's expansion would directly affect Russia's
national interests and would inevitably lead to new division lines
in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said it was necessary to adjust NATO to new political
conditions in Europe, including cooperation with Russia.
</P>
<P>
NATO's expansion was under discussion in the Organization for
Cooperation and Security in Europe (OSCE), ahead of its
forthcoming Lisbon summit, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
