<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador: Cairo Offers Multi-Entry Visas To </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli businessmen now can
get a single "multi-visa" for as many visits to Egypt as they
want in any six-month period, the Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Egyptian Ambassador Mohammed
Bassiouny in Tel Aviv Wednesday. The news was greeted with
delight by some 30 top businessmen, who had expressed concern
about what they called bureaucratic difficulties of traveling to
Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador called on all sides to exert great efforts to
make the forthcoming third Middle East and North Africa Economic
Conference a major success.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt will be proud to hold the conference next month," said
Bassiouny. "I believe that you recognize the economic potential
of the Middle East. In spite of all the challenges, which we do
not exaggerate nor underestimate, there are bridges which could
be crossed."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador indicated that as the host, Egypt is waiting
to see the response abroad before clarifying how many domestic
companies will take part.
</P>
<P>
"Not less than 300 Egyptian businessmen will participate," he
said.
</P>
<P>
So far 3,000 people from the international business community
have accepted invitations to attend, with 700 company
confirmations and 99 countries sending government delegations.
</P>
<P>
A number of Israeli businessmen canceled or refused to
attend the summit out of concern about the political atmosphere
and personal safety.
</P>
<P>
While the number of companies attending the conference is
increasing, there is still uncertainty about participation at the
 political level.
</P>
<P>
It now seems increasingly likely that Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu and other world leaders will be invited to attend the
conference, according to Israel's Foreign Ministry deputy
director-general Oded Eran.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Egypt Edward Walmer, who is now in Israel,
said that Secretary of State Warren Christopher is likely to
lead the U.S. delegation, but the matter would depend on the
outcome of the U.S. presidential election scheduled to take
place on November 5.
</P>
<P>
The first two summit conferences were held respectively in
Morocco's Casablanca in 1994 and Jordan's Amman in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
