<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonia Reaffirms Need For UNPREDEP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA. October 24 (Xinhua) -- Macedonia today restated its
reasons for requesting the extension of the mandate of the United
Nations Preventive Deployment Force (UNPREDEP) in the former
Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
The Macedonia Information Center reported that the Macedonian
Foreign Minister, Ljubomir Frckovski, said the U.N. Force had set
a good example in conflict prevention.
</P>
<P>
The minister was speaking at the closing ceremony of a seminar
on "preventive diplomacy".
</P>
<P>
Frckovski called the U.N. peacekeeping mission the "Macedonian
Model". He said it had accumulated a wealth of experiences and
supplied a firm ground for preventive diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
He also repeated the three reasons for the extension. Firstly,
areas along the border between Macedonia and Yugoslavia's Kosov
province, populated mainly by ethnic Albanians, remained tense
even after the Dayton peace agreements on Bosnia was signed last
November.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, territorial disputes between Greece and Turkey were
another source of instability. Thirdly, the Macedonian army did
not have the capability to defend the republic's northern and
southern borders.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, in Skopje, capital of Macedonia, was attended by
deputies from more than 40 countries. It focused on how to prevent
military conflicts.
</P>
<P>
An international conference on Europeanization and harmony
among Balkan neighbors would be held in Macedonia in January
1997, and attended by U.N. Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali
and leaders of European Union member states, the foreign minister
said..
</P>
<P>
In response to a request by the Macedonian government, the
U.N. Security Council recently agreed to extend the UNPREDEP
mandate for six months, from November 31.
</P>
<P>
The 1,100-member UNPREDEP, at the invitation of
newly-independent Macedonia, was deployed in late 1992 along the
country's northern and eastern borders because of fear of the
Bosnian war spreading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
