<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Predicts Oil Price Drop Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian oil specialist
predicted a price drop in the world oil market in 1997,
saying the oil price would fluctuate between 17 and 21 dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Hojjat Ghanimi, Director of the National Iranian Oil Company
(NIOC), said that the oil prices in the coming year would not be
much higher than in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Persian daily Akbar quoted him as saying that "there are
projections that the price of North Sea Brent crude would
swing round 17-21 dollars and no more."
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran should not take for granted artificially
high oil prices at present for next year's economic planning. The
recent rise in oil price in the international market has been
caused by political rather than economic factors.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the oil price hike in the past few weeks to
tension in the Persian Gulf, Baghdad's push into the Kurdish
occupied northern Iraq, the approaching U.S. presidential
elections, early cold spell in the northern hemisphere and the
drop in stockpiled oil in the industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The oil price hike could be also due to the massive
paper trading of oil in the international energy market, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the second largest oil exporter in the world,
which pumps 3.7 million barrels of crude and exports 2.5
million barrels of crude every day in line with the OPEC
quota.
</P>
<P>
Iran is expected to earn an oil export revenue of 18
billion dollars this year -- about 2 billion dollars more than
the previous projection thanks to oil price hike in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
"There are strong indications in the market that the oil
exporting countries should not be very optimistic about the
continuation of the present oil prices for the next year,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
