<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit to Private Sector Declines in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Credit expansion in
Pakistan's private sector fell 10 percent in 1995-96 from that in
1994-95, said the annual report of the State Bank of Pakistan
released in the southern port city of Karachi today.
</P>
<P>
The report said credit expansion in the private sector in
1995-96 was 60.3 billion rupees (1.51 billion US dollars) during
1995-96, compared with 66.3 billion rupees (1.66 billion dollars)
in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
The report said credit through commercial banks, which
represents core segment of credit to support the private sector's
production activities, increased to 54.9 billion rupees (1.37
billion dollars) in 1995-96 from 49.7 billion rupees (1.24 billion
dollars) in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
Of the overall credit disbursement to the private sector, loans
of 5 billion rupees (125 million dollars) were disbursed by
commercial banks to the agriculture sector.
</P>
<P>
Major Pakistani commercial banks disbursed 7 billion rupees
(175 million dollars) to the private sector's manufacturing
industry as fixed investment finance during 1995-96, up 75 percent
from the 4 billion rupees (100 million dollars) in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
Credit to small businesses increased to 600 million rupees (15
million dollars) in 1995-96 from 300 million rupees (7.5 million
dollars) in 1994-95, while credit to small industries fell to 3.1
billion rupees (77.5 million dollars) from 4.5 billion rupees (113
million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
