<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Delegation to Visit Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A delegation of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) will arrive here soon for
discussions on the release of the second tranche of its loans
under the 600 million dollars standby arrangement.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said here today that "the delegation is
expected to reach here either on Friday or Saturday" and is likely
to stay here for two to three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The IMF is to hold talks with Pakistan's government officials
and complete its review on the country's economic performances
before presenting it to the IMF executive body in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The executive body will then deliberate on the review, and in
case of a positive conclusion, the release of 80 million dollars
will stand approved "immediately," the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the tranche will be made available
immediately as no new agreement is required to be signed.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources admitted that it would take a few days to
complete the transaction.
</P>
<P>
The IMF had refused in March to release the second tranche of
the standby arrangement, signed in October last year to bail out
Pakistan from its economic difficulties, due to its
dissatisfaction with the country's economic performances.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan sent two delegations to Washington for talks with the
IMF after failing to persuade the IMF to send a delegation to
Pakistan to review its economic performances, as required every
three months for the release of the loan.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, the IMF put forward tough conditions,
including a huge cut in government expenditures, increases in
taxation and containing budget deficit to four percent of the
gross domestic product, for the release of the loan.
</P>
<P>
The news of the IMF forthcoming visit came after the Pakistani
government announced a rational economic reform package on
Tuesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
