<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Free Air Market Brings Cheaper Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Europe's free air travel
market has delivered cheaper fares, new airlines and a wider
choice of routes, but there is more room for improvement, a study
says.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission (EC) has published a report of its
study of the impact of the third and final stage of
liberalization, from 1993 to 1996, to assess progress so far and
outline future action.
</P>
<P>
The EC Transport Commissioner, Neil Kinnock, said more work
was needed to ensure that the traveling public was better served
at lower cost.
</P>
<P>
The number of air routes had increased, monopolies broken up,
20 new airlines had opened for business and fares had fallen since
1993, when the EC dismantled national barriers to air travel, and
began the final stage of opening Europe's air transport up to
competition.
</P>
<P>
Given the drop in the ticket prices for many scheduled routes
and the fact that the charter market accounted for more than half
the total market, around 90 percent of all passengers now
traveled on cheap fares, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The EC's approach to creating a single market in European air
travel, first launched in 1987, was deliberately phased in three
stages to avoid the market disruption experienced in the United
States "Big Bang" approach to liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The last barrier will fall in Europe in April 1997, after which
any EU airline may fly between two points anywhere in the Union.
</P>
<P>
However, Kinnock pledged to use EU legislation for prizing open
those sectors of the market which still remained closed to open
and free competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
