<HEADLINE> Tomba Misses First First Leg of Alpine Skiing Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- SOLDEN, Austria, Oct 24 (AFP) -
Triple Olympic champion Alberto Tomba will miss the start of the
alpine skiing season -- as usual -- when two giant slaloms are
scheduled in Solden, Austria this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Italian prefers to join the series when it gets underway
properly in December but an injury in training ruled him out
anyway.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old, who has changed his mind about retiring for
the second year running, injured his left knee and right wrist.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 World Cup winner, who has twice won the Olympic grand
slalom gold and a gold in the slalom, said his decision to
continue had been influenced by the fact that Italy will be
hosting the world championships next February at Sestriere.
</P>
<P>
The favourites for Sunday's race will be Michael Von Grunigen,
who won five of nine giant slaloms last season, and fellow Swiss
Urs Kaelin, runner-up to Tomba in last season's world
championships in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Austrian-born Marc Girardelli, the 33-year-old who races for
Luxembourg, starts his 18th year on the World Cup circuit he has
won five times.
</P>
<P>
Also in the starting lineup is Norwegian Lasse Kjus and
Austria's Mario Reiter.
</P>
<P>
Kjus, the 1993 world champion and 1994 Olympic champion, was
runner-up to Girardelli when he won his third World Championship
combined title in February.
</P>
<P>
Reiter, nicknamed the 'ice eater', won the Sestriere slalom and
Furnao giant slalom last season.
</P>
<P>
Tomba may be absent but his compatriot Deborah Compagnoni, the
world and Olympic champion, will start her year-long campaign for
the overall title against German stars Katja Seizinger, the World
Cup holder, and Martina Ertl.
</P>
<P>
Seizinger, Olympic downhill champion, also won the super-giant
World Cup last season.
</P>
<P>
Austria's Anita Wachter, whose win here in 1993 led to her
overall World Cup triumph, is looking up again at 29.
</P>
<P>
Wachter, took a year to recover from the death of her best
friend Uli Meier who broke her neck in a fall at Garmisch in 1995,
has recovered from an operation after tearing ligaments in her
left knee in training in February.
</P>
<P>
But women's skiing will be without Switzerland's Vreni
Schneider, one of the most successful racers of all time, who
retired last season.
</P>
<P>
In 11 years on the slopes she won three Olympic gold medals,
three World Cup overall titles, three world championship victories
and 54 World Cup races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
