<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Offshore Oil Output to Reach 14 Million Tons This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China's offshore oil and gas
wells are expected to produce a record 14 million tons of crude
oil and three billion cubic meters of natural gas this year,
marking a major breakthrough for the nation's 14-year-old offshore
oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Production already reached 10 million tons, a record high, by
September this year, according to the China National Offshore Oil
Corp (CNOOC).
</P>
<P>
Chinese vice-premier Zou Jiahua today told a national
conference commending model workers of the offshore oil sector,
that China's offshore oil sector has typically boosted the
national industry with high speed and good efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The booming offshore oil sector has greatly benefited from
large-scale Sino-overseas cooperation, and CNOOC's own efforts,
the vice-premier added.
</P>
<P>
According to CNOOC president Wang Yan, China has so far
verified offshore oil and gas geological reserves of 1.25 billion
tons and 240 billion cu m, respectively, with 17 oil fields and
two gas fields operational offshore.
</P>
<P>
Through four rounds of international bidding and numerous
negotiations, CNOOC has signed 119 oil and gas contracts with 65
overseas oil companies from 18 countries and regions, absorbing a
total overseas investment of 5.24 billion US dollars, or 58
percent of China's total for the offshore oil sector.
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC president disclosed that China will build another 10
oil and gas fields offshore in the coming five years, including
eight run by CNOOC itself.
</P>
<P>
The senior official added that between 2000 and 2010, the
average annual oil and gas output to be generated by the existing
offshore oil and gas fields will be stabilized at 12 million tons,
and 15 billion to 20 billion cu m, respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Climbs the Sixth Highest Peak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A 43-year-old Russian has
scaled Mt. Dhaulagiri-I, the world's sixth highest peak, the
Nepalese tourism ministry said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Mochnikov, 43, of St. Petersburg reached the top of
8,163-meter summit through the northeast ridge on Monday.
Mochmikov is the leader of the 12-member Russian team.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a member of the Japanese Himalayan Expedition,
36-year-old Masahiro Nagasako of Tokyo, reached the top of
Mt. Pumori on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Nagasako and his sherpa guide reached the 7,161-meter peak from
the southeast ridge route.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese government banned two Belgians from climbing for
10 years after they attempted to scale 8,848-meter high
Mt. Qomolangma without permission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
