<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Able to Feed Its People: Vice-Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Jiang
Chunyun said here today that China is able to rely on itself to
feed its 1.2 billion people.
</P>
<P>
Meeting participants in Beijing at a Sino-US seminar on
agricultural science and technology, Jiang said China has scored
remarkable developments in agriculture since the founding of the
People's Republic in 1949, particularly since the implementation
of reforms and opening policy in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Jiang added that China's agricultural economy is growing in an
all-round way, and the farmer's living standards have been greatly
improved.
</P>
<P>
He said China, during the ninth Five-year-plan period
(1996-2000), wishes to secure steady output increases in grain,
cotton, oil-crops and other essential agricultural produce, while
ensuring a faster increase in farmers' income. China will also
provide enough food for the 65 million people who are still living
below the poverty line, he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier noted that China will always take agriculture
as a top priority of the country's economic development.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China will deepen rural reform, rely on
science and technology to boost agriculture, strive for a
sustained development, and strengthen international exchanges and
cooperation in agricultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Jiang welcomed agriculture experts from foreign countries,
especially those of Chinese origin, to conduct more academic
research and exchanges in China.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier congratulated the convening of the seminar,
which has attracted 31 American and Canadian agriculture experts
of Chinese origin.
</P>
<P>
He said the suggestions made by the experts will benefit
China's agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
Lee-Shin Tsai, a researcher from Western Regional Research
Center, and some other scholars at the meeting, briefed the
vice-premier on the program of the four-day seminar, which is
scheduled to end on Saturday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
