<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Kuchma Agree on Black Sea Fleet Division </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and his visiting Ukrainian counterpart, Leonid Kuchma, reached an
agreement here today "concerning all questions related to the
problem of the Black Sea Fleet."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's spokesman, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, said the two
presidents also agreed that in the first half of November, Russian
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin would visit Kiev to sign a
package of agreements associated with the fleet's division, and
relevant financial issues.
</P>
<P>
The agreements were reached at the Barvikha sanatorium outside
Moscow, where Yeltsin is preparing for heart surgery in November.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Yeltsin was planning to sign the
long-anticipated "big" treaty on friendship and cooperation
between Russia and Ukraine. It would be done during a visit to
Kiev, as soon as he recovered from the operation.
</P>
<P>
The visit would be Yeltsin's first trip abroad after the
planned operation. It would become possible only after the
comprehensive treaty was completely prepared for signing and all
questions relating to the problem of the fleet were resolved.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma arrived in Moscow earlier this morning and left the
Vnukovo-2 airport directly for the sanatorium to meet Yeltsin. He
was expected to meet with Chernomyrdin later today.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian president told reporters at the airport that
Russia and Ukraine were "as close as ever to signing a big
political treaty."
</P>
<P>
He was accompanied by his Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko and
Deputy Minister of Foreign Economic Relations and Trade Igor
Podolev. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
