<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French National Railway Loses Massively </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned National Railway
Company of France (SNCF) suffered a loss of 7.5 billion francs
(1.5 billion U.S. dollars) in the first six months this year, the
SNCF management said today.
</P>
<P>
The company was also expecting a net loss of 12.5 billion
francs (2.5 billion dollars) for the whole of 1996, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
The SNCF sales figures for the first half of 1996 amounted to
27.475 billion francs (5.5 billion dollars), a 0.7 percent drop
compared with the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The SNCF, after years of losing money, might have to adopt an
austerity plan to keep running.
</P>
<P>
More than one-third of the SNCF employees joined the national
strike on October 17 to protest the austerity plans of Prime
Minister Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
The unions of state-owned companies are opposed to Juppe's 1997
budget which will cut the government deficit to less than three
percent of the nation's gross domestic product, a prerequisite for
joining the European Monetary Union in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The latest government belt-tightening measures include plans
for the privatization of the Thomson SA electronics group, the
Compagnie Generale Maritime shipping company, and the Air Liberte
company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
