<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Hold International Conference on Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait will hold an
international conference on November 18-20 on the impacts of the
Gulf War in 1991 on the environment in the Gulf region and other
parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
A fax transmitted to Xinhua today by the Kuwait Institute for
Scientific Research (KISR), which is one of the conference
organizers, said that the meeting, the first of its kind in
Kuwait, aims to "provide an opportunity for experts from the Gulf
and other parts of the world to exchange current information on
the regional and global implications of the Gulf War."
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Gulf region, the U.S., Britain, Japan and
other countries are expected to take part in the meeting, which
will be organized by the KISR, some other Kuwaiti research
institutes and petroleum establishments and the Gulf Cooperation
Council General Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf War triggered off by the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in
1990 led to the attack on Iraq by U.S.-led allied forces. The war
resulted in one of the worst environmental catastrophes in the
history of mankind. About 6 to 8 million barrels of crude oil was
released into the marine environment.
</P>
<P>
Around 800 oil wells in Kuwait remained burning for several
months after the end of the war, emitting huge quantities of
pollutants to the atmosphere. And 60 million barrels of crude oil
gushed from the burning wells created oil lakes over a vast area
of the desert land.
</P>
<P>
The damage to the desert environment has also resulted from
trenching and movement of heavy military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, several national and international environmental
agencies have participated in the monitoring of pollution caused
by the war. Experts and scientists have also attempted to assess
the global and regional impacts and predict future problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Publishes Text Book on Law for Cadres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A text book was published in
China today to educate Party and government officials on the
country's legal system.
</P>
<P>
The book's preface was written by the General Secretary of the
Chinese Communist Party Central Committee and Chinese President
Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
Jiang urged that "all cadres, especially leading cadres at
various levels, must take the lead in learning knowledge of law".
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for our cadres to do a good job, and to
enhance the ability of leadership, and proficiency of management,
as well as necessary for us to lead the broad mass of the people
to learn the knowledge of law, use the law and consciously abide
by the law," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
"To learn knowledge of law must be included in the rules for
cadres," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Justice Minister Xiao Yang said at a ceremony marking
the release of this book that "The goal for the rule of law, and
the construction of the socialist legal system set by the central
authorities, mean that the political, economic and social lives,
and all the work of the state, should be administered according to
law and certain standards step by step," he said.
</P>
<P>
It also means that the democratic system must be guaranteed by
the law, he said.
</P>
<P>
Wu Lianyuan, deputy head of the Organizational Department of
the CPC Central Committee, said at the meeting that the party
officials have been showing an increasing zeal in studying the
law, following repeated calls by Jiang and other top party
officials.
</P>
<P>
"But we must clearly realize that because of the influence of
the feudalist ideology, rooted for thousands of years, and
old-fashioned traditional concepts, especially the chaotic
situation and flagrant violations of law and order in the period
of the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), a considerable number of
our cadres have a weak understanding on the concept of the rule of
law," Wu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"Quite a few comrades are not used to, or not good at seeking
legal methods to deal with their work, so that illegal activities
of replacing the law with personal arbitration, blocking
law-enforcement with personal power, in addition to illegal policy
making, and illegal judgements, are frequently found," he said.
</P>
<P>
in certain cases, "the legitimate rights of the people are
violated, major economic losses were suffered by the state and
collectives, and the image of the party is harmed, and relations
between the party and the people are adversely affected," he
warned.
</P>
<P>
"Intensifying education for the officials on the knowledge of
the law is by no means a hollow slogan," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ren Jianxin, director of the Political Science and Law
Committee of the CPC Central Committee, was editor-in-chief of the
book.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Introduce Business Visa Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
announced here today that his country will implement a new type of
business visa next year for member economies of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC).
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the Philippines will introduce APEC business visa in
1997 "with multiple-entry privilege, valid for five years, which
is meant exclusively for bona fide business people". He added that
the visa shall be offered on "a reciprocal basis" to all APEC
economies.
</P>
<P>
The president made the above remarks when accepting a report
presented by the APEC Business Advisory Council (ABAC) which
called on the APEC leaders to promote freer business travel in the
Asia Pacific region among other recommendations.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Ramos also accepted the ABAC proposal to set
up special business immigration lanes at major Philippine ports
of entry to reduce border restrictions.
</P>
<P>
He said the creation of the business visa and special
immigration lanes in major ports will facilitate travel to the
Philippines by business executives from other APEC members.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier before that Australia raised the idea
of creating a visa-free smartcard that ensures free move for
accredited businessmen in the APEC region, but some APEC members
opposed the proposal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
