<HEADLINE> Chinese, Uruguayan Foreign Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen held talks with Uruguayan Foreign
Minister Alavro Ramos in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers exchanged views on bilateral
relations and international issues of common interest and reached
agreement on a variety of topics.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the past few years, since the two countries
established diplomatic relations, have seen great development of
friendly cooperation and exchanges in all fields.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides supported, and cooperated with each other in
international affairs, and enjoyed good relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government is willing to work together with
the Uruguayan government, with a forward-looking vision, to bring
out a long-term, stable, and mutually beneficial, friendly and
cooperative relationship.
</P>
<P>
Expressing joy over his first visit to China, the Uruguayan
foreign minister said his government attaches great importance to
its relations with China.
</P>
<P>
The two countries share many points of view, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We both hold that any country, big or small, rich or poor,
should be an equal member of the international community; we both
abide by the fundamental principles of international law, such as
non-interference in other's internal affairs and settle disputes
through peaceful means."
</P>
<P>
Ramos said Uruguay would like to expand and intensify its
cooperation with China in every field. He reiterated that the
Uruguayan government will, as always, sticks to its "one China"
stand, and will continue to fully support China's entry into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers were satisfied with the development of
bilateral economic and trade ties, and pledged to make joint
efforts to push forward cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to actively encourage the establishment of joint
ventures, and various forms of economic and technological
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said Uruguay can serve as a bridge for the development of
China's relations with the South Cone Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
Ramos arrived here today on a week-long visit to China at the
invitation of Qian. 
</P>
