<HEADLINE> Ramos Reaffirms Objection to Constitution Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today reaffirmed his objection to any constitutional amendment to
lift his term limit or extend his six-year term.
</P>
<P>
Meeting a media group here this morning, Ramos said that he has
nothing to do with the reported moves for "a people's initiative"
in provinces, including his home province of Pangasinan, to amend
the constitution to extend the term of the president and other
elected officials.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine constitution, Ramos cannot seek a second
term and will have to retire in June 1998 when his term ends.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that he is looking forward to retirement and a role
as "an elder statesman."
</P>
<P>
However, he said that "under our democratic system" he could
not stop people from initiating moves to amend the charter.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that even if he were to go on the radio and
television for a whole day to assert his opposition to any
constitutional amendment, "people will always do their thing."
</P>
<P>
A campaign for constitutional amendments is underway in the
country while opposition forces are accusing Ramos of
masterminding the drive.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
