<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Urges Immediate Implementation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
today urged all parties in the Arab-Israeli peace talks to
implement "completely and immediately" the agreements reached so
as to push the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
"The agreements reached must be implemented fully and without
delay," said the visiting French president in his address to
Jordan's parliament here today.
</P>
<P>
He also called for more negotiations between the Arabs and
Israelis and expressed his support for an independent Palestinian
 state.
</P>
<P>
"There must be negotiations, and still more negotiations,
until all the problems related to the final status are settled,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Chirac, who is on his seven-day official visit to the Middle
East region to salvage the stalled peace process, gave a vivid
description of "a reconciled Middle East" in his address.
</P>
<P>
"A reconciled Middle East, with the co-existence of a
peaceful and prosperous Palestinian state, an Israel accepted by
all and freed of the threat of terrorism, a Hashemite Jordan, an
example of democracy and development, a Syria in full control of
all its territory and at peace with its former enemy, a Lebanon
completely free, sovereign, dynamic, and a strong and wise Egypt,
a pioneer of peace," the president told Jordanian lawmakers both
in the Upper House and the Lower House of the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of peace in the region, saying
that "if there is no peace, there will be no security."
</P>
<P>
He also voiced his confidence that it is possible to save and
win peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
"I remain convinced that our march towards peace is
irreversible," he said, adding that "despite the tragedies, the
obstacles placed on our path, the efforts of the extremists, I
believe it is possible to save the peace. I think it is possible
to win the peace."
</P>
<P>
Chirac, who is on his mission to promote a French and
European effective role in the peace process, said his country
will not suggest to the parties "the clauses of a treaty,"
adding that France will give advice on the principles on which a
lasting peace should be based.
</P>
<P>
The principles, he said, are "the exchange of land for peace,
the exercise by all countries of the region of their sovereignty
over the whole of their territory, security for all... (and) the
free determination by the Palestinians of their own future, in
other words the foundation of a state."
</P>
<P>
On Iraq, Chirac expressed his country's concern over Iraqi
humanitarian situation, and pressed the international community
to implement U.N. Resolution 986, which provides for the
resumption of Iraqi oil exports against the purchase of food and
medicine in order to save the Iraqi people from tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Franco-Jordanian relations, he described the
ties between the two countries as "strong and trustful," noting
that his country will continue press for the association of
Jordan with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries can work for peace "side by
side."
</P>
<P>
"Through our dialogue and joint efforts, peace can move
forward, because Jordan is a central actor in the stability of
the region," he said before the parliament.
</P>
<P>
The French president arrived here late Wednesday and will
leave for the Lebanese capital of Beirut after concluding his
two-day official visit to the kingdom later today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
