<HEADLINE> Red Star Over China Still Shining: Edgar Snow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The 60th anniversary of visit
to northern area of Shaanxi province by Late American journalist
Edgar Snow, known as the writer of "Red Star Over China", was
commemorated at Beijing University today.
</P>
<P>
The event was hosted by the China Society for People's
Friendship Studies (CSPFS) and the China Centre on Edgar Snow
Studies.
</P>
<P>
Snow, who once worked in the university, arrived in Bao'an in
northern Shaanxi province in June, 1936, which was the site of
the Chinese Red Army.
</P>
<P>
After interviewing Chinese revolutionary leaders and the
Chinese Red Army, Snow compiled the noted book.
</P>
<P>
And he still wrote books about China after the People's
Republic of China was established in 1949, which promoted US-Sino
relations and the friendship between people of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The CSPFS President, Huang Hua, said that it was necessary to
learn from Edgar Snow to train more qualified reporters and
editors in China.
</P>
<P>
Vice chairmen of the Standing Committee of China's National
People's Congress Lei Jieqiong and Cheng Siyuan, Chairman of US
Edgar Snow Memorial Foundation Grey Dimond, along with teachers
and students of Beijing University, attended the event.
</P>
</TEXT>
