<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Weakens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar weakened
against major currencies today.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 79.23 US cents from 79.54 US
cents on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was pulled down by an increasing
possibility of an interest rate cut before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) announced today that
the full-time adult average weekly ordinary time earnings
increased by 0.7 percent in the three months to August, making an
annual rate of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figure fell into the lower end of market expectations,
which centered around an increase of one percent. The wage
increase figure was viewed as a leading indicator of inflation.
</P>
<P>
ABS figures released yesterday also showed that inflation rate
fell to 2.4 percent annually from 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister John Howard and Treasurer Peter Costello hailed
the figures as good news for the economy and called for the
Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) to cut interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar softened in the expectation that the
interest rate differential between Australia and other western
countries was likely to shrink.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 89.34 yen against the Japanese
yen from 89.73 yen yesterday.
</P>
<P>
It was also weaker against the German mark, ending at 1.2053
marks from 1.2143 marks on Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
