<HEADLINE> European Parliament President's Meeting with Dalai Accused </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China today made a stern
protest against and expressed its strong dissatisfaction about a
meeting between the Dalai Lama and presidents of European
Parliament and Commission of European Union.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Shen Guofang outlined
details of the formal protest this afternoon at a press conference
in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Shen said Tibet is an inalienable part of Chinese territory,
and Tibetan affairs are purely China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
"No foreign government, parliament, organization or individual
person has any right to intervene," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Shen, Dalai, who decks himself out as a religious
person, has been engaged in political activities outside China for
a long time, in an aim to separate the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Presidents of the European Union Commission and European
Parliament were bent on meeting Dalai, disregarding
representations and firm opposition by the Chinese side many
times, he said, adding that the European Parliament even offered a
forum for Dalai to openly support and instigate Dalai's separatist
activities. Their acts, he noted, have interfered with China's
internal affairs, and seriously hurt the feelings of the Chinese
people.
</P>
<P>
Shen said China has expressed strong dissatisfaction, and
lodged a stern protest to the European side.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, relations between China and Europe
could only be established on the basis of mutual respect and
non-interference with each other's affairs. Any act in the other
direction will bring damage to the healthy development of
bilateral relations, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
China requests that European Union institutions and their
leaders earnestly abide by its stand of "acknowledging Tibet as a
part of China's territory", and set the general interests of
Sino-European relations above everything else, not instigating,
and supporting the Dalai group in their separatist activities,
Shen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
