<HEADLINE> S. Korea's Opposition Leader Gets 18-Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Lee Yong-hee, leader of a main
opposition party, was sentenced to one-and-a-half years in prison
and fined 116,000 U.S. dollars for bribery here today.
</P>
<P>
Handing down the sentence, Seoul District Court Judge Park
Tong-yong said Lee's involvement in a graft case deserved a
prison term in view of his status as a political leader.
</P>
<P>
Lee, vice president of the National Congress for New Politics
(NCNP), was accused of receiving 116,000 U.S. dollars from Chin
In-kwon last June when Chin was running for the superintendent of
the Seoul Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
Chin allegedly gave the money to Lee with a request that the
NCNP vice president ask two education board members, Ahn Jang-kang
and Park Jun-sik, to vote for him. He also gave 61,000
U.S. dollars each to the pair in bribes in return for their
support.
</P>
<P>
Lee was arrested on bribery charges on September 9. The
prosecution had requested a four-year prison term for Lee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
