<HEADLINE> CPC Leader Meets Nepalese Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Rongji, a Standing
Committee member of the Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist
Party (CPC) Central Committee, met with a delegation from the
National Democratic Party (NDP) of Nepal here today.
</P>
<P>
Zhu extended a warm welcome to the delegation, led by NDP
chairman Surya Bahadur Thapa. The visit is the first NDP trip
abroad at the invitation of a foreign political party.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said there exist long-lasting friendly relations between
China and Nepal. Bilateral relations have developed smoothly since
the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949 and
China-Nepal relations can been seen as a model of good-neighborly
ties between two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the newly-established relations between the CPC and
the NDP are established on the principles of independence,
equality, mutual respect and non-interference into each other's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
He added that such relations will help further enhance the
friendly relations and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, also China's vice-premier, thanked the Nepalese government
and the NDP for their consistent support given to China on the
Taiwan and Tibet issues.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed the visitors on China's economic development.
</P>
<P>
Thapa said he is happy to see that China has scored rapid
economic development while maintaining social stability.
</P>
<P>
On the Taiwan and Tibet issues, he noted the NDP has always
held that Taiwan and Tibet are unseparable parts of the Chinese
territory.
</P>
<P>
He added that the NDP oppose any attempt which is aimed at
Taiwan or Tibet independence.
</P>
<P>
Thapa said the Nepalese people will never forget the consistent
support and help China has offered to Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The NDP delegation started their China visit Wednesday at the
CPC's invitation. 
