<HEADLINE> Chinese Defense Minister Meets Philippines Army Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Defense Minister Chi
Haotian said here today that China and the Philippines have all
reasons for cooperation and no reasons for confrontation.
</P>
<P>
Chi made the remarks at a meeting with general Arturo
T. Enrile, chief of staff of the armed forces of the Philippines,
in the Great Hall of the People.
</P>
<P>
"China and the Philippines have one thousand and ten thousand
reasons to strengthen exchange and cooperation and have not a
single reason to trigger off confrontation," Chi said.
</P>
<P>
Chi, also vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission and
State Councillor, said China and the Philippines are good
neighbors. To maintain and develop the momentum of the bilateral
friendly relations, including the exchanges between the two
armies, benefits not only the two peoples but also peace,
stability and development in the region, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
China and the Philippines have the similar history in the past
and common interest at present, and face the same task of building
up their respective countries, Chi added.
</P>
<P>
Chi said he was happy that the exchanges between the two armies
have been conducted at a higher level. he said that Enrile is the
first chief of staff of the Philippines armed forces to visit
China. His China trip, Chi added, would advance the relations
between the two armies and the two countries as well.
</P>
<P>
While briefing Enrile and his party on China's economic
development, Chi said China would not practise expansion or power
politics even after it becomes much stronger economically.
</P>
<P>
"China has stationed not even one soldier overseas and China's
national defense policy is entirely defensive. In any sense, the
so-called 'China Threat' is just totally groundless," Chi stressed.
</P>
<P>
Enrile said he was honored to meet minister Chi and believed
his China trip would have positive role in reinforcing the
friendship between the two armies and pushing ahead the bilateral
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Enrile and his party were here as guests of Fu Quanyou, chief
of the general staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army. Fu
hosted a welcoming ceremony for Enrile this morning, and met with
and feted the Philippines guests in the evening. 
</P>
