<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, British Experts Meet on HK Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group (JLG) today started their 20th expert meeting on
defense and public security in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Chinese JLG representative Chen Zuo'er told a press briefing
that the major subject of the meeting was the discussion of the
advance party of the HK garrison troops of the People's Liberation
Army.
</P>
<P>
He also confirmed that the Chinese side has, at the experts
level, unofficially informed the British side of the drafting of
the Garrison Law.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that the task of the advance party is to make various
preparations for the PLA garrison troops to smoothly take over
Hong Kong's defense on July 1, 1997, instead of assuming the
defense responsibility in advance. The British side will remain
responsible for Hong Kong's defense until June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the advance party is an important part of the
smooth transfer of Hong Kong's defense. As there are only more
than 200 days before the transfer, it is necessary for the two
sides to make concerted efforts to speed up the pace of work.
</P>
<P>
In response to questions, Chen pointed out that issues
concerning the Garrison Law will not be discussed at the JLG
expert meetings, because the formulation of the law is purely
China's domestic affair.
</P>
<P>
He said that the formulation of the Garrison Law will lead to a
comprehensive legal system of the garrison troops in HK which
fully reflects the principle of "one country, two systems", so as
to ensure that PLA garrison troops will carry out their defense
responsibility according to the law.
</P>
<P>
He said that as provisions of the Garrison Law belong to the
national defense and related affairs administered by the Central
People's Government, it is the right of the Central Government to
draft the law.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, considering that the law will be implemented
in the future Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), and
some of its provisions will have direct or indirect relations with
the SAR government and local residents, the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress will, while deliberating the law,
listen to the opinions and suggestions from Hong Kong in
appropriate forms.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, many good ideas from Hong Kong people have been
considered or adopted during the studying and drafting of the
Garrison Law," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
