<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Reports: Nigeria's budget deficit Surpasses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Nigeria
Wednesday reported a fiscal deficit of about 82 million
U.S.Dollars in the first half of the 1996 national budget, about
seven weeks after a surplus of 100 million Dollars was declared
for the same period by the Finance minister.
</P>
<P>
The deficit, representing about 0.4 percent of the Gross
Domestic Product, was attributed largely to the outlay on debt
servicing which is above the amount budgeted for, and the
shortfall in the projected revenue from the autonomous foreign
exchange market (AFEM) surplus, the Central Bank report said.
</P>
<P>
In its ''Economic Report For The First Half Of 1996'', the
Central Bank said the difference between the figure of the
Central Bank and that of the federal Finance Ministry is
accounted largely for:
</P>
<P>
''While the ministry recorded 22 billion Naira (275 million
Dollars) and six billion Naira (75 million Dollars) for external
and domestic debt service payments respectively, actual payments
in the central bank indicated 26.804 billion Naira (335 million
Dollars) and 120 billion Naira (1.5 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
''Secondly, the statutory share of the federal government from
AFEM intervention surplus held with the Central Bank was 26.783
billion Naira (335 million Dollars) as against 31 billion Naira
(388 million Dollars) reported by the ministry.''
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Central Bank report said, the outstanding
public debt of the federal government at the end of June this
year fell by 0.6 percent to 1.1 billion naira (13.75 million
dollars), representing a debt ratio of 62.1 percent compared with
78.4 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
''The domestic debt components fell by 6.6 billion (82.5
million Dollars) or 1.6 percent at 402.9 billion Naira (5.04
billion Dollars) at the end of june 1996, while the external debt
outstanding declined marginally to 31.9 billion Dollars from 32.5
billion as at December 1995,'' the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
according to the central bank, the total actual external debt
service payments during the first half of this year anounted to
1.2 billion dollars, representing 23.07 percent of the projected
annual debt service payment.
</P>
<P>
The main goals of the government's fiscal policy in 1996 are
to strengthen the fiscal position of the federal government and
stimulate private sector activities through aggressive revenue
drive, public sector expenditure restructuring and tax
incentives.
</P>
<P>
The budget aimed at achieving a surplus of 19 billion Naira
(238 million Dollars) or 1.15 percent of the Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) at current market prices, as against the 6.8
billion Naira (85 million Dollars) or 0.5 percent of last year's
GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
