<HEADLINE> Bevilacqua Sets to Quit Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Top Italian high jumper Antonella
Bevilacqua will quit athletics because of a longstanding doping
controversy.
</P>
<P>
Bevilacqua, fourth in the Atlanta Olympics, twice tested
positive for the stimulant ephedrine during May and June, but was
cleared by the Italian Athletics Federation (FIDAL).
</P>
<P>
FIDAL accepted she took the susbtance, which was contained in a
herbal medicine, without knowing. However, her case is still in
arbitration with the International Amateur Athletic Federation.
</P>
<P>
"She's given up, and she's got my full support," said her
mother and coach Maria Sigillino. "Her name is now forever
associated with doping and it's had a devastating effect on her.
</P>
<P>
"She's exhausted. Being linked with drugs is something really
serious, it's a mark which is going to stay with her forever. So
it's better if she gives up athletics and everybody forgets about
her."
</P>
<P>
Bevilacqua's sister Marcella said: "She hasn't trained since
coming back from America. She's just devoted herself to her
studies and has already taken three exams at the Academy of Fine
Arts."
</P>
<P>
However, Italian sports officials have not given up hope on
Bevilacqua, whose case was recently switched by the IAAF's
arbitration panel from October 26 to November 25. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
