<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Tourism Receipts Up in The First Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The total Tourism receipts in
Hong Kong posted a double-digit growth during the January-June
period, boosted by a surge of expenditure by visitors from North
and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The total receipts went up about 18 percent this year as the
end of June from a year earlier to 40.9 billion HK dollars (5.3
billion US dollars), according to the Hong Kong Tourism
Association. The total for 1995 was 75 billion HK dollars (9.7
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
North Asia, including Japan and the Republic of Korea, topped
the list of spending among major market areas. Spending by
tourists from the two countries amounted to 9.3 billion HK
dollars (1.2 billion US dollars) in the first half of this year,
up 38 percent over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Shopping continued to be the most popular category for
expenditure by visitors to Hong Kong, accounting for half of their
total spending.
</P>
<P>
The association forecasts that total tourism receipts this year
are likely to hit 85 billion HK dollars (10.9 billion US dollars),
registering a 13-percent rise over 1995.  
</P>
