<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Bans Insurance Broker from Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Insurance brokers in China's
largest city have been given a caning - for flooding Shanghai's
middle and primary schools with insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
School children and students have virtually been forced into
signing up for policies because of the hard-sell actions of the
brokers.
</P>
<P>
Now city officials are to hand out a tough lesson by ordering
the closing of school doors to all of the enthusiastic insurance
brokers, under a newly-issued official circular.
</P>
<P>
"People are permitted to buy insurance policies on a voluntary
basis, but the activities of some insurance companies in schools
goes seriously against the rules, which in turn has smeared the
reputation of the business," says the People's Bank of China's
Shanghai Branch. It has warned all the insurance companies in the
circular.
</P>
<P>
The circular said that insurance brokers in schools seriously
interfered with the students' normal lives, and imposed pressure
on students because buying insurance policies has become a 'must'
in some schools, instead of a voluntary act.
</P>
<P>
All the insurance companies have been banned from handing out
any insurance leaflets, survey forms, and policies in schools in
the circular, which also ordered the companies to immediately
withdraw policies and refund students when required.
</P>
<P>
Brokers who have breached the rules will receive an offical
warning and be fined 10,000 yuan. Their business activities will
also be suspended for three months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
