<HEADLINE> Health Meeting Points to Total Tobacco Ads. Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Speakers at an international
conference opened here today called on a total ban on tobacco
advertising so as to bring the Western Pacific to a
tobacco-advertising-free region.
</P>
<P>
The two-day 1996 conference on smoking and health gives a clear
signal that the participants are striving for materializing the
goal by the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
"At the heart of the WHO Western Pacific Region Action Plan on
Tobacco or Health 1995-99 to fight against tobacco use is a call
for a 'Tobacco-advertising-free Region by the Year 2000," said
S.T. Han, Regional Director of the World Health Organization
(WHO) Regional Office for the Western Pacific, at the opening
ceremony today.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first of its kind here, is organized by the
Hong Kong Council on Smoking and Health with the support from the
WHO Regional Office.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that we have to protect our populations, especially
our young people, from the influence of advertising and the
effects of direct and indirect advertising through sponsorship of
sport and cultural events," Han added.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the decreasing of smoking population in Hong Kong over
the last 13 years, from 23.3 percent in 1982 to 14.8 percent in
1995, there is a rising trend of smoking among young people and
women," said Katherine Fok, Hong Kong's Secretary for Health and
Welfare.
</P>
<P>
"Although the percentage of teenaged smokers is low, the trend
is nonetheless worrying," she said.
</P>
<P>
"Tobacco control is an area where there is no rooms for
complacency and the government takes the problem of smoking,
especially among youth, very seriously," she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
