<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Continue Peace Effort in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has not abandoned
its peace efforts in Afghanistan, which focused on a ceasefire
among the warring factions, a Pakistani Foreign Office spokesman
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference, the spokesman said that
Pakistani Interior Minister Nasirullah Babar, who visited
Afghanistan six times recently, had brought the Taliban and the
three-party alliance led by Rashid Dostum closer.
</P>
<P>
"But the ousted Afghan government troops led by Ahmad Shah
Masood demanded the inclusion of "demilitarization of Kabul" as
part of the ceasefire agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
"That condition is a new thing with which the Taliban have not
come to grips as they have not yet thought about it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, the spokesman said the condition of
demilitarization of Kabul has held up the proposed ceasefire
agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said, "it could be unrealistic at this point of time but we
are not shutting our mind on any issue as it is possible we may
come at a stage where demilitarization is defined in such a manner
when both sides find it acceptable."
</P>
<P>
Replying to another question, the spokesman said that the U.N.
special envoy to Afghanistan Nobert Holl is currently meeting
Taliban leaders in Kandahar, the Taliban headquarters in southern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We are now waiting for the outcome of Holl's talks with
Taliban leadership," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
