<HEADLINE> Small Towns Help Rural Areas in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- As more farmers find work in
non-agricultural sectors in east China's Zhejiang Province, the
provincial government has come up with a series of measures to
increase construction of small cities or towns.
</P>
<P>
It has also set up a group in charge of comprehensive reforms
in small towns, and has household registration reforms in six
townships. Economically developed towns account for a third of the
province's total output value, and small towns are bringing
greater prosperity to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has encouraged local governments,
collective firms, and individuals to invest in developing towns.
</P>
<P>
Wukang Township, in Deqing County, used to be a small
village. In the early 1990s, it became the county seat and
developed a series of policies to encourage departments or
individuals to invest in Wukang's development. After five years, a
new township was erected on barren hills, and the government's
input in the new township was not more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new hi-tech and private industry zone in Wukang has not
only reduced industrial smoke that caused pollution, but has also
saved large tracts of farmland.
</P>
<P>
With the favorable policies, small towns have mushroomed in
Zhejiang. Statistics show that there are now 965 cities and towns
in the province, six times more than the figure for 1978.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
