<HEADLINE> Caspian Sea States to Divide Seabed Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Five deputy foreign ministers
from Azerbaijan, Iran, Kazakhstan, Russia and Turkmenistan
gathered here today in a bid to iron out their differences on how
to divide the seabed resources of the oil-rich Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Georgy Mamadov, Iranian Deputy
Foreign Minister Mahmoud Vaezi and their counterparts from three
other neighboring countries participated a two-day meeting of the
Caspian Sea littoral countries on legal regime of the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The five deputy foreign ministers will prepare a joint
statement, which will be signed and announced in the foreign
ministerial meeting in Ashkhabad, Turkmenistan, in November.
</P>
<P>
The Caspian Sea, the largest land-locked lake in the world, is
rich in oil and gas resources. It has an estimated 75 trillion
cubic meters of gas and 150 billion barrels of oil reserves.
</P>
<P>
In the face of the rich resources, the five littoral states
want to launch development projects.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said at a press
conference held here today that there are three ideas of dividing
the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
Russia supports the idea of giving a 20-mile continental
shelf to the sharing countries.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan maintains to divide the seabed among the five
littoral states.
</P>
<P>
There is a call for extending the continental shelf to 40
miles instead of 20 miles and sharing the rest among the littoral
states.
</P>
<P>
Velayati said in the opening address that it is imperative for
the littoral states to work together to draw up appropriate legal
regime for setting the scopes and limits of the sovereignty of
states for rich resources.
</P>
<P>
"I am of the firm conviction that given the political
determination that the littoral states have so far demonstrated,
problems of the Caspian Sea and its legal regime will be
resolved," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft copy of the joint statement to be signed
by the foreign ministers, the five littoral states will conclude
a convention on the basis of the agreement by all the Caspian
states on the legal status of the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The convention will incorporate fundamental principles of
regulations of issues of navigation, the use of biological and
mineral resources, environmental protection as well as
sovereignty rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Welcomes Chirac's Visit to Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz today expressed his welcome to the current visit by French
President Jacques Chirac to the Middle East, saying that the visit
demonstrated France's "new dynamism" in handling problems in the
region.
</P>
<P>
During his ongoing tour of the region, Chirac has visited
Syria, Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas. He will also
visit Lebanon and Egypt before winding up his tour of the region.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in his office, Boueiz said that
Chirac's visit to the region demonstrated France's new dynamism in
handling problems and crisis in the Middle East and in
clarifying France's position on establishing peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that France's position on calling for peace gave it a
"bigger size" after absenting from the Middle East arena in the
past years.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that Europe and France should play a role in the
region with which they have common history and old relations,"
the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 Madrid peace conference which brought for the
peace process, France has been demanding an effective European
role, the Lebanese foreign minister said. "Today, we do welcome
this role," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on what happened to the French president in the Old
City of East Jerusalem Tuesday, the Lebanese minister noted that
different views had come up since Chirac started his visit in the
region.
</P>
<P>
In what was called by Chirac a "provocation," Israeli security
men jostled the French president and manhandled journalists as he
was touring East Jerusalem, and Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu apologized afterwards.
</P>
<P>
"It was clear yesterday (Tuesday) that the Israeli authorities
were attempting to prevent President Chirac from contacting, or
at least shaking hands with the Palestinian people who were
welcoming him," Boueiz said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Israel had refused to allow a visit by
Chirac and his Foreign Minister Herve de Charette to Orient
House, the PLO headquarters in East Jerusalem, "since it regards
the visit as a recognition of the Palestinian state."
</P>
<P>
Describing Chirac's position as "brave," Boueiz underlined
that the position "expressed France's openness and feelings
toward the friendly peoples in the world and rights of the
ill-treated and oppressed peoples."
</P>
<P>
During his Middle East tour, the second of its kind in six
months, the French president repeatedly said that Europe
should have a role in the peacemaking in the region, and that
there could be no security in the region without full peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
