<HEADLINE> Hussein, Chirac Call for Honoring Signed Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Hussein and
French President Jacques Chirac called here today for a complete
and immediate implementation of the signed agreements among all
the parties concerned in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state made the appeal during their talks at
the Royal Palace here shortly after Chirac arrived in Amman
from the West Bank town of Ramallah for his first official visit
to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders discussed bilateral relations and the Middle
East peace process in all aspects, especially means of salvaging
the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Hussein lauded French efforts and vital role in the peace
process, saying that France is dedicated to achieving a just,
comprehensive and durable peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian monarch also praised France for its "courageous
initiatives and just, principled stances regarding world events
and the various issues affecting the peoples in the region."
</P>
<P>
People in the region "look for an active and supportive
European role," he told Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The king expressed appreciation of the help and support France
has extended to Jordan in the past decades.
</P>
<P>
"We are particularly grateful for France's firm and unwavering
 support throughout all the hardships Jordan and the region
endured through decades of conflict," said King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The king reiterated Jordan's commitment to a comprehensive
peace based on international legitimacy and relevant
U.N. resolutions. He called for international collective efforts
to achieve peace and reap its benefits.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-French talks started with closed-door
discussions between the Jordanian king and the French president,
which were followed by an enlarged meeting attended by senior
officials from both sides. 
