<HEADLINE> South Korea to Join OECD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Foreign Minister
Gong Ro-myung left here today for Paris to sign an agreement on
South Korea's entry into the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
This came at a time after the OECD Council officially invited
South Korea to join the club of advanced countries on October 11.
Seoul applied for membership in March last year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister will sign the accord with OECD
Secretary-General Donald Johnston. He will also speak on South
Korea's plan for cooperation with the existing 28 OECD members.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean government plans to submit a bill on OECD
entry to the National Assembly for ratification next month.
</P>
<P>
The ruling New Korea Party (NKP) has expressed support of the
country's accession to the OECD, while the opposition parties
voiced the concern that the free flow of capital and other market
opening measures will seriously disturb South Korea's domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
South Korea will become the 29th OECD member when it deposits
an admission document with the French government after its
parliament ratification before December 25.
</P>
<P>
During his week-long visit to Europe, Gong will also visit
Luxembourg to sign a framework cooperation agreement and a joint
political declaration between South Korea and the European Union
(EU) with his EU counterparts and Leon Brittan, vice president of
the EU commission, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The two documents will lay the legal groundwork for a
comprehensive partnership between South Korea and the EU, a
Foreign Ministry official said here.
</P>
<P>
Following the signing of the two documents, Gong and EU foreign
ministers will hold the 12th Korea-EU ministerial meeting which
will seek to enhance bilateral and multilateral cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
