<HEADLINE> Lebanese FM: Middle East Peace Process Still </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz said here today that the peace process in the Middle East
was still "suspended" in spite of so much "side activities aimed
at keeping the hope and making the cooked food remaining on fire."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on an optimism expressed by Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu on the Syrian-Israeli peace talks, Boueiz said
that the statement was only aimed at cheating the public media.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac, who is currently touring the
region, delivered a message Tuesday to Netanyahu from Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli prime minister described the message as "positive,"
but declined to disclose its details.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that what was stated by Netanyahu was not a move for
gaining time, nor another action for propaganda which Netanyahu
has accustomed us in the past months," the Lebanese foreign
minister told a press conference in his office.
</P>
<P>
He repeated a call for the resumption of the peace
negotiations between the Jewish state on the one side and Syria
and Lebanon on the other without returning to the zero point.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that there is really a fundamental progress and that
Israel is seriously and essentially ready for the negotiations
and for a returning to what had been reached in the era of
(former Israeli prime ministers) Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres,"
the Lebanese minister said.
</P>
<P>
But there was no serious signs which "allow us to say that
Israel has a new positive style for returning to the peace
process," he said.
</P>
<P>
After taking office in June, the hardline Israeli prime
minister called for a resumption of peace talks with Syria
without any precondition.
</P>
<P>
Damascus asked Tel Aviv to make a commitment to a withdrawal
from the Golan Heights before the deadlocked peace process is
re-started.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish state suspended the negotiations with Syria in
March following a series of suicide bombings in Israel. 
</P>
