<HEADLINE> Arab League Chief Warns Against Israel's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdul-Meguid has said Israel could not possibly be
incorporated into the regional economic bloc before freeing the
Middle East from its nuclear threat.
</P>
<P>
Israel's nuclear arsenal, which is not under international
supervision, constitutes a threat to Arab security, disrupts
regional balance and threatens stability and peace in the region,
Meguid said in a lecture at the Nasser's Military Academy here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There were many reports on Israel's nuclear arsenal. But Israel
has neither admitted nor denied the possession of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Abdul-Meguid noted that Israel has secured many gains from the
peace process since 1992. "The number of states recognizing
Israel has risen to 165 from 85," he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's exports have doubled while foreign investment
multiplied six-fold hitting 2 billion U.S. dollars annually, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Israel's GNP grows by about 6 percent and the number of
tourists soared from 2.5 million in 1992 to 7.6 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, Abdul-Meguid said Israel's belligerent policies have
bred a spate of economic difficulties, citing the 14 percent
inflation rate, the mounting deficit in balance of payments,
increasingly unbalanced foreign trade and the government's
free-hand expenditure.
</P>
<P>
"The recent Israeli policies would only make it harvest the
fire of a renewed Palestinian intifada (uprising)," Meguid warned.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League chief rejected Israel's "security for peace"
slogan as invalid and described the "land-for-peace" principle as
the sole formula to realize peace and security in the Middle
East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
