<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 10:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Security Services Warn of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
security services are working together to try to foil an attempt
by Islamic Jihad to carry out a suicide bombing attack, Israel
Radio reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
As of midnight, Israel clamped a closure on the entire West
Bank and Gaza Strip and put its security forces on special alert
amid warnings that the Islamic Jihad would stage the attack at
the end of October to mark the first anniversary of the
assassination of its late leader, Faithi Shkaki.
</P>
<P>
Shkaki was shot and killed last October in Malta. Islamic
Jihad members accused the Israeli Mossad secret service of
carring out the assassination. But the Mossad neither denied nor
claimed the responsibility.
</P>
<P>
Syria-based Islamic Jihad leader Ramadan Shallah has recently
declared that he wanted to damage the peace process, and avenge
the death of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai ordered the closure
following special consultations with Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, chief
of general staff of the Israeli army, and top security officials.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said that the open-ended closure is expected to
last until at least after Saturday, October 26. Shkaki was
assassinated on the same date last year in Malta.
</P>
<P>
During the indefinite closure, all Palestinians are barred
from entering Israel from the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestinian VIPs, 270 medical personnel working in
east Jerusalem and rare humanitarian cases will be permitted in,
provided they have the approval of the Israeli government's
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yigal Pressier, Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu's
adviser on combating terrorism, has urged the public to be
particularly alert this week and report anything suspicious.
</P>
<P>
A senior security source told Israel Radio that security has
been beefed up throughout the country with police setting up
roadblocks to thwart any attack.
</P>
<P>
"We know that late October is the date they are intending to
attack," the source said, "all the security services are taking
measures to foil this, including speaking with the Palestinian
Authority (PA)."
</P>
<P>
He added that the PA is cooperating with the Israelis and is
carrying out arrests in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
Israel Television Channel 1 said Wednesday night that the
Palestinian police had detained 15 Islamic Jihad activists in
the Palestinian autonomous areas, who were reportedly planning
attacks against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israeli police sources said that security measures, which
included roadblocks on the Tel Aviv-Jerusalem highway Wednesday
morning that snarled traffic for hours, will remain in effect at
least during the coming days.
</P>
<P>
Police Inspector-General Assaf Hefetz issued a statement
calling on commuters to understand the nation's security needs
and the public to look out for suspicious objects and persons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
