<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China's Female Drop-outs Back to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 girls who
dropped out of school have returned to school in Zhejiang
Province, thanks to help from a charity program.
</P>
<P>
The Spring Bud Plan, which was started by the China Children's
Foundation in 1992, provides free primary-school education and
room and board for extremely poor girls from rural areas.
</P>
<P>
To put the plan into work, the women's federation in the
province's Pingyang County made an effort to collect 600,000 yuan
last year to pay for the girls' books, school meals, and housing.
</P>
<P>
The federation also called on people from all walks of life to
sign a one-on-one commitment with the girls to provide support for
their education.
</P>
<P>
Many people not only offer financial help to the girls, but
also treat the girls as if they were their own children.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the county has set up 19 Spring Bud foundations to
develop basic education for rural girls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
