<HEADLINE> 2 Nigerians Sentenced in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Two Nigerians involved in a
cheating scam have been sentenced to six-year imprisonment each in
Singapore and became the first Nigerians convicted here for
cheating charges, police said today.
</P>
<P>
The two Nigerians, James Peter Ojemen, 28, and Hassan Baba, 29,
were said to have tried to cheat one million US dollars out an
Indonesian businessman by making him believe he could earn
millions.
</P>
<P>
They lured the man to Singapore by fax and tried to sell him a
chemical solution which they claimed could clean blackened US
notes into legal currency.
</P>
<P>
Police investigations also revealed that they faxed similar
messages to Taiwan, Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Judge Tan Siong Thye said that the Nigerians, by choosing to
commit the crime here, tarnished Singapore's international
reputation as a safe place with low crime rates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
