<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Temple For Chinese Minister With 10 Million Descendants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The temple of a Chinese prime
minister of about 1,000 years ago, known for having produced 10
million descendants, has been restored in Shaowu city, in Fujian
province.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qiao held office during the Five Dynasties (907-979) and
had three wives who gave birth to 24 sons for him.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents record that, on his 82nd birthday, he sent
21 sons away, telling them to develop their own lives, marking a
break from the tradition of people living with their family
members nearby.
</P>
<P>
A thousand years passed, and Huang's offspring could be found
living in many southeastern coastal areas of China, in Taiwan, and
in Southeast Asia, and numbered about 10 million. Taiwan alone
boasted 1.25 million of them.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 of his descendants have come to Shaowu to
visit their ancestral home in the past few years, and have donated
more than one million yuan to restore the temple that commemorates
him.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qiao's tomb has been recognized by the city as a
historical marker since 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
