<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Acadmeic activities are expected to
resume from Monday in Nigeria's 34 universities, with the announcement
of yesterday by the banned Academic Staff Union of Universities (ASUU)
to end its six-month strike.
</P>
<P>
ASUU had on April 9 called out its members nationwide on a strike,
after a series of weekly warning strikes failed to persuade the
federal government to meet is demand for improved working conditions,
adequate funding of universities and autonomy for the institutions.
</P>
<P>
The decision was reportedly made by the National Executive
Counil of the ASUU upon receiving positive signals from the government
on its major demands and that negotiations will continue.
</P>
<P>
However, Chairman of the Academic Staff of Lagos State
University Ojo Olorundleke was quoted as saying yesterday that the
decision was taken in the interest of the students and concerned
Nigerians who had been appealing for an end to the strike. 
