<HEADLINE> Thai Parties Spend Heavily on Election Campaigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's political parties
contesting the November 17 general election are spending heavily
to ensure their candidates' election and advertise themselves as
the most suitable to lead the country.
</P>
<P>
Observers predict that more than 20 billion baht (800 million
U.S. dollars) will be spent in the run-up to the polls, on "buying
up" former members of parliament, vote-buying and all sorts of
public relations campaigns.
</P>
<P>
The figure was higher than the about 17 billion baht (680
million dollars) spent in the July 2 general election last year.
</P>
<P>
Political canvassing will also bring windfalls to television,
radio, newspaper and printing firms which produce or carry
advertisements and posters.
</P>
<P>
The New Aspiration Party and the Chart Pattana (Thai
Development) Party, which are contesting in the northeast, are
vying with each other for voter support by spending large sums of
money to project themselves as the national rather than regional
leader.
</P>
<P>
The Democrat Party, on the other hand, focuses on its perceived
strength of honesty and professionalism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
