<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Fifth Hanoi Residents to Have Telephone in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 24 (Xinhua) - The Hanoi post office has set a
goal of 20 telephones per 100 Hanoi residents by 2000, according
to its deputy director Tran Khai Lai.
</P>
<P>
Hanoi now has some 180,000 telephones. The number will rise to
210,000 by the end of this year or equal to about eight units for
every 100 people, which is the highest rate of subscription in the
country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some 100 public card phones are operating in the
more densely populated areas of the city.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the fixed telephone network, there are also two
mobile phone systems operating in Hanoi. The Vietnam Mobile
Services (VMS) has 11,000 subscribers after two years of operation
while Vinaphone has 1,400 after four months of operation.
</P>
<P>
The number of mobile phone subscribers in Hanoi is expected to
increase to 18,000 by the end of this year, Lai estimates.
</P>
<P>
Lai said the Hanoi post office planned to put a network of
radio-linked telephones into service by the end of this
year. Indonesia has pledged 40 million U.S. dollars to the
project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GDP of Three Central Asian Nations Picks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and Uzbekistan is picking up this
year for the first time since the collapse of former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that the GDP of Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and
Uzbekistan increased by 0.1 percent, 0.3 percent and 1.4 percent
respectively for the first half year of 1996, compared with the
same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output of the three Asian Nations increased by
0.2 percent, 13.2 percent and 1.4 percent respectively, the Asian
Economy and Life Weekly said.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural output of the three countries continued to
decline this year, with a margin of 14.5 percent, 12.6 percent and
2.1 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
But the grain production of the three nations increased, with
kazakhstan totaling 13.1 million tons, 2.5 million tons more than
last year, Kyrgyzstan becoming one of the few countries which do
not need importing grain among the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
In foreign trade, Kazakhstan's import and export volume
increased markedly, with export increasing by 56 percent and
import 21 percent. Uzbekistan's export increased by 4.8 percent
and import 19 percent. Kyrgyzstan's export declined by 15.8
percent and import increased by 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
Since the collapse of the former Soviet Union, close economic
links between the member states of CIS have been destroyed.
Consequently, their economies plunged into crisis. Between 1991
and 1995, GDP of the CIS member states declined continuously, with
the average rate of 10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
