<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-German Team Probes Mystery of Terra-cotta Warriors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-German team has
discovered a purple chemical compound in the paint of the
terra-cotta warriors and horses in northwest China's Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
Scholars say that the find will help in preserving the
terra-cotta figures that served as guards in the afterlife of Qin
Shi Huang Di, who united China and set up the Qin Dynasty (221-206
BC).
</P>
<P>
The joint archaeological team also discovered that the wood
used in the shelter over the figures was fir, dragon spruce,
Chinese hemlock, and elm, and that chalk accounted for the bulk of
the clay used in the pit where the figures were put.
</P>
<P>
That is a clue for further study of the warriors, scholars
noted, without giving any details about what that meant.
</P>
<P>
The archaeologists have also co-operated in conservation work
with rare relics found in Famen Temple in the province, where
Sakyamuni's bones were enshrined in the Tang Dynasty (618-907) and
some 1,000 pieces of relics were found in an imperial tomb of the
Northern Zhou Dynasty (557-581).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese Island Large Orchid Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- South China's Hainan province
has become the country's largest orchid producer.
</P>
<P>
Its 30-hectare tropical orchid farm in Chengmai county
cultivates 300,000 potted orchids for sale in major Chinese
cities, Japan, and Southeast Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In addition to more than 100 species of wild orchids native to
Hainan, the farm has succeeded in breeding some 500 species of
precious orchids imported from overseas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
