<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comfortable Housing For Chinese Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Construction work has begun on
a 13.5-million-yuan teachers' village in Puding, a poor county in
southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the cash-strapped province has given priority
to eduction and helped more than 13,000 teachers move into new
apartments, and the 2.3-hectares village is meant to solve the
housing problem for 300 teachers in the mountainous region.
</P>
<P>
A dozen cities are now building teachers villages for education
improvements in the Puding way.
</P>
<P>
Before 1990, housing shortages were a common phenomenon in
Guizhou, with teachers' living space in the province 20 percent
less than the country's average.
</P>
<P>
In Kaili City, capital of the Qiandongnan Autonomous Prefecture
of Miao and Dong ethnic groups, the living space for teachers
stayed at three square meters for a long time, ranking last in the
province.
</P>
<P>
Since 1994, the city has built two villages for teachers in the
urban district, solving the housing problem for 147 of them. By
1998, per capita living space of the teachers' families will reach
10 square meters, provincial government officials say.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new villages in the province are located in lovely
settings and are close to stores, hospitals, and sports and
recreation facilities. Some have telephones and closed circuit
television.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province set up a housing foundation with 10
million yuan (about 1.2 million US dollars), and gave preferential
treatment to reduce construction costs for teacher villages.
</P>
<P>
The province has also lent support to teachers in rural areas
in building new houses so that they will feel more comfortable in
teaching.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
