<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book-Hungry Peasants Satisfied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A lorry pulled up in a remote
Chinese village in central China's Hunan Province, ready to
offload its supplies to eagerly awaiting peasants.
</P>
<P>
Soon the vehicle's supplies had all be snapped up - and some
people had to go away empty handed.
</P>
<P>
But this was no food-aid program, the lorry had brought a load
of books to villagers in Loudi Prefecture hungry for knowledge.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of books were sold soon after they were unloaded from
the vehicle, and one peasant even handed over his last four yuan
to an official, earnestly wanting to buy a book on
poultry-breeding.
</P>
<P>
This was a scene in Shatang Village, Shuangfeng County, Loudi
Prefecture, where local people did not have easy access to books.
</P>
<P>
The official was moved by the peasants' craving for books. The
prefectural government conducted a survey of 1,200 rural
households. It showed that some 93 percent of households were
eager to buy books.
</P>
<P>
A campaign to send books to peasants' homes was then launched
in the prefecture.
</P>
<P>
To date, the prefectural government has provided a direct
service for over 800,000 people, which includes selling books,
offering economic information, and setting up libraries and
cinemas.
</P>
<P>
The prefectural government has also organized various training
causes to help peasants learn applied science and technology, as
well as related laws.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
