<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing's Financial Market Opens Wider to Outside </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is leading China in its
213 representative offices of overseas financial organizations, with
seven foreign banks setting up branches in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, when the city introduced the first commercial
overseas financial organization, the Mitsubishi Bank of Tokyo, Hong
Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation, Citibank, Hong Kong Nanyang
Commercial Bank, Industrial Bank of Japan, Korea Exchange Bank,
and First National Bank of Chicago, have all opened branches in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The branch banks had 1.07 billion US dollars in assets by
August this year, 2.8 times the 1995 figure, and 260 million US
dollars in balances held on deposit, 2.3 times the 1995 figure.
</P>
<P>
The branches mainly provide services, covering foreign exchange
deposits, credits and remittances, loans guarantees, and
settlement of import and export accounts, to local overseas-funded
enterprises, foreigners, overseas Chinese people and compatriots
in Hong Kong and Macao.
</P>
<P>
The branches also conduct services of settlement and sale of
exchange for local overseas-funded enterprises, becoming the
country's designated foreign exchange banks.
</P>
<P>
Outstanding loans of the branches rose 240 percent over 1995 to
reach 380 million US dollars in October this year, 340 million US
dollars were granted to local overseas-funded enterprises, and
accounts for 30 percent of total loans granted to local
overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of presentative offices of overseas financial
organizations in Beijing has given impetus to the inflow of
overseas funds to the city, improving the local financial reforms
by enlivening its financial market.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to take steps to introduce more commercial
overseas financial organizations, to increase varieties of
services, to form a local diversified financial market, led by
Bank of China and enriched with overseas-funded sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demise of Foreign Fast Food in East Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Four fast food restaurants
from outside China in Hangzhou, the capital of Zhejiang Province
closed their doors in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, an American fast food restaurant in the
downtown area of the tourist city, which specialized in fried
fish, went under, and two months before that, another American
fast food restaurant was replaced by a Chinese one specializing in
soy-bean milk.
</P>
<P>
Two others are advertising for someone to buy them out.
</P>
<P>
"It might be because of the prices or taste," said Chen Weimin,
a Chinese partner in the fried fish restaurant. "In a word,
foreign fast food finds it hard to get in with the common people."
</P>
<P>
Chen is planning on opening a hot pot restaurant on the site of
the dried fish restaurant.
</P>
<P>
The failing restaurants usually operated for about three
years. In the first half year after opening, they seemed quite
promising and many people would come in to see the well-decorated
restaurants out of curiosity. But soon the novelty wore off.
</P>
<P>
"We've found no way to keep the old customers," one owner said
gloomily.
</P>
<P>
While all this is taking place, some Chinese-style fast food
stalls are booming: "In the past, we did not pay much attention to
comfort, or the environment, or standardized service," a manager
of a Chinese fast food restaurant said. "It is the foreign fast
food restaurants who taught us all this."
</P>
<P>
Having taught their Chinese counterparts about advanced
management techniques, the foreign fast food people were finally
forced out of the market one after the other because of
unacceptable prices or taste, Wang Lida, member of the Drinks and
Food Association of Hangzhou, commented.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
