<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workplace Accidents on Rise in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Work-related accidents in Vietnam
are on the rise with 94 incidents causing 120 deaths in the first
six months this year, latest issue of Vietnam Investment Review
reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the review, the death toll of work-related
accidents during this period increased almost three times over the
same period in 1995 with only 34 deaths recorded.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Nguyen An Luong, Vice President of the
Vietnam General Confederation of Labor (VGCL) as saying that the
real figure of death toll was in fact much higher than the
recorded one since 20 provinces did not report the labor accidents.
</P>
<P>
Luong said most of the accidents reported were from state-run
enterprises especially those related to high-rise construction,
high voltage power lines and coal mines.
</P>
<P>
According to Luong, the main cause for fatal accidents was the
violation of working regulations. Moreover, the safety and health
standards in working places have got little improvement although
labor code has been implemented for one year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
