<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuchma, Yeltsin to Meet Over Black Sea Fleet Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma arrived here this morning to meet his Russian counterpart,
Boris Yeltsin, for the long-disputed Black Sea Fleet issue,
Yeltsin's press officers said today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, agreed by the two leaders over a phone talk on
Monday, is scheduled to be held at 12:00 local time (GMT 08:00) in
the Barvikha sanatorium near Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The Black Sea Fleet, a major former Soviet fleet, is based on
the Ukrainian Peninsula of Crimea. Russia and Ukraine both claimed
it after the former Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Ukraine have reached a tentative agreement on
dividing the fleet, but there have been disputes over the status
of Sevastopol, the headquarters of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma expressed the hope that the agreement would be confirmed
during the upcoming meeting with Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
The problem will be resolved soon, Kuchma told visiting Russian
Deputy Prime Minister Valery Serov in Kiev on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, an informed Kremlin source said on Wednesday that the
Russian leadership did not share optimism with the Ukrainian side.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the scheduled meeting, the state Duma, Russia's
lower house of parliament, adopted a resolution claiming that the
fleet was Russia's property and banning the disputed division of
the fleet.
</P>
<P>
The source also said that the Russian leadership is going to
continue the talks on the division and base of the fleet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Use "BOT" to Build Water Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China will use a development
method known as "build, operate and transfer" (BOT) to introduce
foreign investment in its water supply projects.
</P>
<P>
Under the BOT method, projects are built by foreign private
capital and then transferred to China after several years of
operation.
</P>
<P>
Experts agreed it is a good way to build infrastructure in
China, where because of its rapid unbanization, about 300 major
cities are facing shortages of basic necessities such as water.
</P>
<P>
They discussed the topic on a seminar co-sponsored by the
Ministry of Water Resources and the Asian Development Bank, which
ended Wednesday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government favors the BOT method for water-related
infrastructure in urban areas because it can help lighten the
financial burdens of construction, Zhang Chunyuan, vice-minister
of water resources was quoted in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said construction of vital water projects has been
restricted by a lack of adequate State investment.
</P>
<P>
However, BOT can be complicated, since it involves a wide range
of legislative, financial and technological issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
One of the major issues, experts noted, is decentralizing the
approval of such projects from central to local government.
</P>
<P>
They said China could work out regulations governing
decision-making authority by expanding existing rules governing
BOT projects. These include the construction of highways and small
hydrological power stations.
</P>
<P>
The central government has started drafting special regulations
on the use of BOT, an official with the State Planning Commission
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Council, China's highest governing body,
has decentralized the right of approving projects with foreign
investment down to the level of provincial government,
substantially enlarging provincial authority to approve
projects.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Water Resources is also considering
constructing a number of water supply projects with suitable
conditions through BOT as pilot projects fro extension later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fertilizer Production Encouraged in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government has
approved programs to develop the country's fertilizer industry.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam Fertilizer Manufacture's Association (VFMA) said,
Vietnamese farmers can use about three million tons of fertilizer
each year and the demand is still increasing, especially in the
Mekong River Delta.
</P>
<P>
According to the VFMA, Vietnam produced 110,000 tons of urea in
1995, only meeting eight percent of the total demand.
</P>
<P>
Each year, Vietnam spends 250-300 million U.S. dollars on
importing fertilizers from China, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea,
Malaysia, Russia and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Because of the country's dependence on fertilizer imports,
world price fluctuations can adversely impact on both farmers and
importers.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem, the Vietnamese government has endeavored
to encourage domestic fertilizer production, focusing on
microbiological fertilizer used to enrich soil and minimize
environmental pollution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
