<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: New Taxes Incur Strong Reaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Everybody calls them the
"mini-budget," except the opposition which describe them as the
"maxi-budget." And both names are right in a sense.
</P>
<P>
The new taxation measures introduced by the Pakistani
government on Tuesday are a "mini-budget" because they are a
revision of the state budget and they are a "maxi-budget" because
of the heavier taxes to be involved.
</P>
<P>
Whatever the name, the new taxes, to raise badly-needed money
to meet revenue requirements in the state budget for the fiscal
year of July 1996-June 1997, have provoked strong reaction in the
country.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time within one fiscal year that the
Pakistani government has announced tough new measures to increase
taxation and revenue.
</P>
<P>
When the government first announced a 40 billion-rupee (1
billion U.S. dollars) increase in taxation, public reaction was
quick and strong.
</P>
<P>
Various organizations, some of them with the backing of the
opposition, held numerous strikes after the announcement of the
new budget on June 13.
</P>
<P>
The government bowed down, giving concessions of 15 billion
rupees (375 million dollars) to different industrial and
commercial groups.
</P>
<P>
The government, again on Tuesday, announced a tough 40
billion-rupee economic reform package.
</P>
<P>
According to the new package, the government is still in need
of 13 billion rupees (300 million dollars) for its revenue after a
27 billion-rupees (700 million dollars) cut in government
expenditure, most of which in development expenditure.
</P>
<P>
And the money will have to come from new taxes.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural taxes, which the federal and provincial
governments agreed to introduce under the pressure of the
International Monetary Fund, contribute a mere 2 billion rupees
(50 million dollars), according to the new measures.
</P>
<P>
Yet in 1995-96, agriculture-related transactions were worth 600
billion rupees (15 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector, which provides most of the support
needed by the government to stay in power, is capable of
generating around 100 billion rupees if taxed properly and fairly,
according to local experts.
</P>
<P>
Other new measures include an increase in the income tax,
import service charge, foreign travel tax, airport tax and
passport fee.
</P>
<P>
Last but not least is a 10-percent rise in petroleum prices and
gas charge.
</P>
<P>
Along with the new taxation, the Pakistani rupee was devalued,
for the 10th time after the announcement of the new budget in
June, by 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
While announcing the package, "designed to tackle short- and
medium-term problems in the national economic policies," Governor
of the State Bank of Pakistan Mohammad Yaqub said it would help
improve the health of the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
It will not affect the poor, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
The statement is partly true in that that the poor can never
afford to travel abroad or take a flight and thus will not have to
pay the travel tax, airport tax or passport fee.
</P>
<P>
But they can not live without gas, buses, food and many other
essential daily items which have to be imported.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, with a 10-percent jump in petroleum and
gas charge, the trade circles forecast a sharp surge in the prices
of essential commodities within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Polypropylene already set the trend as its prices shot up by
three rupees per kilogram in the wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
Another three rupees are expected to be added to the prices of
plastic raw materials in the next four to five days when new
shipments arrive.
</P>
<P>
The local cotton, rice and yarn markets Tuesday reacted
strongly to the devaluation of the rupee and their prices
escalated instantly.
</P>
<P>
Yarn prices rose by 15 to 20 rupees per bundle and those of
rice by 15 rupees per 100 kilograms while cotton price moved up by
28 rupees per maund at the Karachi Cotton Exchange.
</P>
<P>
"The mini-budget and massive rupee devaluation by the People
government on Tuesday are set to have adverse effect on common
men's kitchen budget," said Chairman of the Pakistan Commodity
Traders Association Rais Ashraf Tar Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
The landed cost of all imports would go up 8.52 percent
immediately whereas the impact of higher petroleum and gas prices
would also push the prices up in a similar ratio when the
commodities reach the consumers.
</P>
<P>
"The essential and semi-essential commodities will not only
become dearer but a shortage resulting from suspension of imports
will further spiral the prices," he warned.
</P>
<P>
With about 21 billion rupees (525 million dollars) or one-fifth
cut in development expenditure, which is the investment for the
future, the development projects are doomed to a serious setback.
The long-term effect could not be felt until five or 10 years
later.
</P>
<P>
However, bureaucrats can continue to enjoy a comfortable life
with endless facilities available to them free of charge as only 6
billion rupees (150 million dollars) will be eliminated from the
current government expenditure.
</P>
<P>
According to a local report, more than 670 million rupees (17
million dollars) is being spent this year on advisers and special
assistants of the chief minister of Punjab province alone.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance reacted quickly by calling for a
country-wide strike on Saturday to protest against the
government's measures. And more strikes could be expected.
</P>
<P>
This, of course, would not help the country out of the present
economic crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya liberalizes Coffee, Tea Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government
yesterday announced major reforms in the coffee and tea sectors,
the "Daily Nation" reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Minister for Agriculture, Livestock
Development and Marketing Simeon Nyachae as saying that the
government's involvement in the two sectors would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the Kenyan government would withdraw
from the Coffee Board of Kenya (CBK) which would become purely a
farmers' organization while only three government accounting
officers remain in the Kenya Tea Development Authority (KTDA).
</P>
<P>
He said growers of coffee and tea were given powers to elect
directors who in turn would choose a chairman and a chief
executive. Previously, the law empowered the Minister for
Agriculture to appoint a chairman from among the directors and a
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform plan, coffee planters and commercial millers
will be free to engage in coffee trade and export at the Central
Auction which remains the only mode of selling coffee in the east
African country.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae noted that the participation of planters and
commercial millers in the coffee trade at the Central Auction
would increase competition and boost efficiency.
</P>
<P>
He said that the KTDA and the CBK will also be restructured by
being exempted from the State Corporations Acts to enable them
take timely and commercially competitive decisions. With the
liberalization of the two sectors, the minister noted, the
government may only intervene in the coffee and tea industry to
make policy guidelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Region Promotes Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region is tapping its beautiful scenery in a bid
to turn tourism into a pillar of the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi is famous for beautiful natural scenes, a rich variety
of unique folk cultures, and home to a number of ethnic minority
groups, with sunny beaches in the city of Beihai at the southern
tip of the region.
</P>
<P>
The region has boosted the construction of new scenic and
holiday sites.
</P>
<P>
A golf course and a scenic zone have been completed in the
famous resort city of Guilin, and the cities of Liuzhou and
Nanning have invested 6.8 million and 15 million yuan respectively
in construction or renovation of tourism zones, scenic spots and
support facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Silver Beach National Tourism Zone in Beihai has introduced
23 projects with a total investment of 46 million US dollars,
which will include the building of shopping, touring and
entertainment facilities, and improvement of the zone's
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi has also accelerated the development of new tourism
markets, especially overseas-backed projects. It has adopted the
strategy of consolidating the traditional markets in Hong Kong and
Macao, and expanding those in southeast Asia, Europe, and the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
Special marketing groups have been sent to international
tourism exhibitions and fairs in Milan, Paris, Hong Kong and
Australia. And the regional tourism authorities have sponsored
special promotion programs, such as the Guilin Tourism Festival.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the region is co-operating with neighboring
provinces and regions, such as Yunnan, Guizhou, Tibet and Sichuan,
in the initiation of 20 travel routes featuring southwest China's
ethnic cultures and customs.
</P>
<P>
The region has also increased supervision of the service
quality of the tourism business, by formulation and implementation
of regulations on hotel and travel services.
</P>
<P>
There are 108 hotels permitted to receive overseas travelers,
164 travel agencies in the region. More than 30,000 local
residents are employed in the tourism business.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 17 years, the region has received more than 6.3
million overseas travelers, and about 90 million domestic
tourists, and earned 994 million US dollars in foreign exchange
and 10 billion yuan from tourism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
