<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's caretaker Prime
Minister Banharn Silpa-Archa said today that the United Nations
should be reformed and revitalized.
</P>
<P>
In a speech marking the United Nations day at the U.N.
Conference Center here, Banharn said his country is convinced that
"in order to fully retain its relevance in today's world, the
United Nations must first be reformed and revitalized, to become
more capable, more representative, more accountable and better
managed."
</P>
<P>
He said, "reforms must be made to restore the confidence of the
international community in the efficacy of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Banharn noted that today "we are increasingly faced with issues
of a transboundary nature, for example, the problem of drugs,
terrorism, human exploitation, severe poverty and refugees, not to
mention international and economic crime, which pose new
challenges to intergovernmental cooperation."
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Thailand's readiness to play its role, as a
member and partner of the United Nations, in the twin missions to
build lasting peace and security, and sustainable economic and
social development throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Heads of the United Nations offices and specialized agencies in
Thailand held United Nations day celebrations today in cooperation
with the United Nations Association of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ambassadors to Thailand attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A pictorial exhibition featuring activities of the United
Nations was inaugurated at the United Nations center, which was
followed by music performance by the royal Thai navy band.
