<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Accepts Proposals of APEC Business Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today accepted recommendations from business leaders of the Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) designed to jump-start the
implementation of the free trade and investment goals for the Asia
Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"With these comprehensive recommendations, APEC is ready to
move from policy to action," Ramos declared when accepting a
report containing the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "APEC Means Business: Building Prosperity
of Our Community," represents the first ever active participation
of the APEC business sector in designing and developing economic,
trade and investment policies for APEC leaders.
</P>
<P>
It was presented to Ramos by the APEC Business Advisory Council
(ABAC), a group of 53 business executives representing all the 18
APEC member economies. It will be discussed when ABAC holds its
first ever dialogue with APEC leaders in Manila on November 24.
</P>
<P>
"This report constitutes a full response to our goal of fully
integrating the business community into the design and
implementation of APEC's current and future work," Ramos added.
</P>
<P>
In the report, ABAC recommended that the APEC leaders promote
freer business travel in the Asia Pacific region by introducing an
"APEC business visa," provide enhanced investment protection to
encourage lower investment financing costs and increase the
private sector's role in the planning, financing and delivery of
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
it also called for strengthening small and medium-sized
enterprises through the establishment of technology exchange
networks and the creation of an enhanced partnership between
public and private sectors through economic and technical
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ramos expressed support for these ideas and announced that the
Philippines will immediately implement some of the
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government will introduce next year a new
business visa to facilitate travel to the Philippines by business
executives from other APEC members.
</P>
<P>
The president also ordered concerned government departments to
plan a Philippine public-private sector infrastructure roundtable
and the establishment of an APEC network for economic and
technical cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
