<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Urged To Stand United on Issue of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Africans should remain
united if they want to be seriously heard on the issue of
biosafety, Ethiopian Agriculture Minister Teketel Forssido said
yesterday at an on-going workshop on the draft protocol on
biosafety here.
</P>
<P>
Teketel said biosafety is not an issue peculiar to Africa, but
it is a problem of all the nations in the south.
</P>
<P>
He called for the countries in the south to get together with
each other to find consensus on the issue of biosafety, adding
that the powerful countries usually may not be comfortable when
the countries in the south function together as a southern block.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Africa is a continent where infant
mortality, illiteracy, war, hunger and diseases are among the
highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said: ''There can be no economic development without a
commensurate technological development as its base.''
"Biotechnology is now being seen as the growth industry of the
21st century. we do not want to be left behind once again,''he
added.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, financed by the Third World Network is being
attended by representatives of 12 African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
