<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Agriculture to Slump Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Grain production in Bulgaria is
expected to drop drastically next year as only half of the
country's planned acreage was planted this fall.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Minister of Agriculture and Food Industry Krastiu
Trendafilov said only 850,000 ha of farmland are planted this
fall, compared with the target of 1.6 million ha.
</P>
<P>
The minister told a national meeting on agriculture that
livestock production was also affected this year by poor harvests
of grain in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The average output of farm produce in Bulgaria in 1995 is one
third of 1992.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, whose agriculture was capable of feeding as much as
three times the population of the country, now has to import grain
to feed its people.
</P>
<P>
Only 15 of the country's 63 pig-raising incorporated
enterprises are operating and the others are being liquidated,
said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria produced 20,000 tons of less pork in 1996 than the
previous year, and the output of egg and dairy products also
dropped, the agriculture minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the failure of agriculture to the
deconcentration of farmland, and destruction of agricultural
infrastructure and the losses of overseas market share for farm
produce.
</P>
<P>
Farmland across the country was divided up to the farmers as
the co-operatives were dissolved by the Union of Democratic Forces
of Bulgaria after it took office in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Much farmland has been deserted in recent years as little
progress has been made in land reform and substantial agricultural
facilities were destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Some members of co-operatives attending the meeting called for
cooperative management of agriculture. They argue that is the only
way to save the country's agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Railway Line to Help Ease Poverty in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China's 898-km-long Railway,
from Nanning, in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region to
Kunming, in southwestern Yunnan Province, has brought new hope to
people living in a 36,000-sq-km area which is known for its
poverty.
</P>
<P>
As the finishing touches are put on the railway, provinces in
the southwest are working on a number of related projects to
alleviate poverty. The Chinese government has a major aluminum
project, an optical fibre cable along the railway, a series of
hydro-electric power stations with a 2.52-million-kilowatt
capacity, and a coal and phosphorus project set to begin soon.
</P>
<P>
The railway is renowned for the geological difficulties it
faced, the heavy workload, the high cost, and the new technology
used, because it goes through mountainous areas with a 1,900-meter
change in elevation.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan, Guizhou and Guangxi provinces have China's richest
bauxite resources, half of China's phosphorus, a third of its
lead, zinc, and manganese, and a fifth of its iron reserves. Their
coal reserves are the combined total of all provinces south of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is determined to build several major
railways no matter what the cost, in these provinces, because it
believes these major communication arteries can help bring in more
capital to develop rich natural resources and eradicate poverty by
the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
The Railway from Nanning to Kunming is expected to help
overcome poverty in the areas alongside it, said Wang Shengye,
deputy head of the Qianxi (southwest Guizhou Province) Prefecture
of Bouyei and Miao Ethnic Minorities. He notes that the greatest
difference between the railway and other poverty relief projects,
is that the project will not only help local farmers but will
provide financial support for counties in the locality.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government plans to use the railway for several
power and mineral development zones, such the Hongshui River
Hydropower and Mineral Development Zone in Yunnan Province, and
the mineral production exploitation zones in Panzhihua and Xichang
in Sichuan Province, and Liupanshui in Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
The railway can also turn the poverty-stricken area into bases
of industries involving coal, iron and steel, aluminum, gold,
building materials, coal chemicals, and phosphorus chemicals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
