<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection at China's Biggest Oilfield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Daqing Oilfield has
improved its environmental protection by removing 820 pollutants
and building 132 waste water disposal plants in the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
The oilfield in northeast China's Heilongjiang Province has an
annual crude production capacity of some 50 million tons. Daqing
spent 444 million yuan (55.5 million U.S. dollars) from 1990 to
1995 tackling pollution problems caused by the oilfield and
petrochemical plants.
</P>
<P>
All polluted water left after oil extraction and 95 percent of
industrial waste water in Daqing are being treated now, and all
new industrial projects are now required to be equipped with
environmental protection equipment.
</P>
<P>
For 407 projects launched in the past five years, 675 million
yuan (84 million dollars) was used for environmental protection
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Daqing has established an enterprise-county-city environment
monitoring system which provides data for the oilfield's
anti-pollution operations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
