<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government, Civil Servants Fail To </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Renewed negotiations between
the Zimbabwean government and civil servants who suspended a
nationwide strike in September, ended in a deadlock on
Wednesday amid threats by the workers to resume industrial action
again.
</P>
<P>
A nine-member government negotiating team led by Public
Service Commission Secretary Lovemore Masoka failed to reach an
agreement with the striking workers after nearly 10 hours of
talks with nine members of the unified civil service negotiating
committee.
</P>
<P>
Six of the seven outstanding issues from the two-week
crippling strike have not been addressed by the government and
this might force the civil servants, who reluctantly agreed to
suspend the two-week strike in September, to take industrial action again.
</P>
<P>
The government only proposed an increase of the funeral
allowance to 550 U.S.Dollars, announced last month by public
service, labour
</P>
<P>
and Social Wellfare Minister Florence Chitauro.
</P>
<P>
The other outstanding issues included bonuses, increases in
various allowances, a unified labour law encompassing all workers
and civil servants.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations reached an impasse when the government which
had since September been postponing the meeting failed to offer
anything concrete on the outstanding issues. Instead, according
to representatives of the civil servants, the government
requested another postponement to November 8 to allow the cabinet to
discuss the six issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
