<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Helping Make Chinese Citizens More Aware of Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A new TV program in China,
Court Fax, is helping increase people's awareness of the law in
northeast China, with live transmissions of cases being tried in
intermediate people's courts.
</P>
<P>
The program provides live broadcasts twice a week from the
coutrooms of Shenyang, capital of Liaoning Province, for the
city's six million residents.
</P>
<P>
In any case, only a small number of people are present in the
court room, whereas the number of potential viewers of the live
broadcasts is enormous. A recent survey conducted by Shenyang TV
showed that the program has become one of the station's most
popular.
</P>
<P>
For the Chinese government, providing knowledge via the mass
media has become an important means of improving the country's
legal structure and citizens' awareness of the law.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that hundreds of Chinese news sources have
begun special legal affairs columns, which have had an enormous
impact on hundreds of millions of readers, and several of the
country's media giants, People's Daily, China National Radio, and
China Central Television (CCTV) have started legal affairs
programs which have become quite influential.
</P>
<P>
In the Tiexi District of Shenyang, a 40-year-old self-employed
worker said: "By watching Court Fax, I have gained lots of legal
knowledge which, I believe, will be beneficial to my future
business life."
</P>
<P>
In 1986, the Chinese government began a publicity campaign on
knowledge of the law around the country, which is now in its
fifteenth year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Media Helping Make Chinese Citizens More Aware of Law (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Awareness of the law has increased remarkably and the notion
that "one can protect his or her rights and interests by resorting
to the law" is becoming widely accepted.
</P>
<P>
The different media now select from a variety of cases,
covering everything from armed robbery to intellectual property
rights, most of which touch the lives of ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
Wan Yuliang, vice-president of the city's Intermediate People's
Court, said that a special phone line set up in the People's Court
is very busy anytime Court Fax is airing.
</P>
<P>
People raise all kinds of questions, asking about certain laws
and regulations, trying to predict the outcome of the proceedings,
and even assessing the performance of the judges, lawyers, and
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
Some experts say they believe that, with the improvement in
China's legal system, such as the increased role of lawyers in
cases, the media are certain to play a greater role in publicizing
knowledge of the law. 
</P>
