<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Changing Relations With Other Parts of China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Municipal
Government says that the city will invest 30 billion yuan (about
3.6 billion US dollars) in other parts of China over the next five
years and industrial output value of its enterprises outside the
city will account for five to ten percent of its total.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest financial and commercial center, is
prepared to move part of its traditional industries to Yangtze
River areas and to the river's delta area, and plans to
collaborate with other areas in developing pillar and hi-tech
industries, setting up three to five industrial parks outside
Shanghai, and establishing 50 inter-regional and multi-trade
enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
The city will also get 5,000 enterprises to set up projects in
the city, encourage 500 large enterprises to set up regional
headquarters, and try to get more foreign trade companies to open
subsidiaries in the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's annual economic growth since 1990 has stayed at 13
percent, a phenomenon not seen elsewhere in the world, but the
city's space limitations and lack of resources have restricted its
development. To deal with this problem, the city has developed an
export-oriented economy and increased ties with other parts of
China.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Shanghai's industrial and commercial
enterprises have established a nationwide sales network, made
investments, bought shares, merged factories, and raised technical
renovation funds to increase their influence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Changing Relations With Other Parts Of China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What characterizes the new relationship most, experts say, is
the marketplace. Shanghai's unique advantages in technology,
information, commodities, and capital are responsible for economic
and technological co-operation between the city and many other
places.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that the new relationship is conducive not
only to Shanghai's development, but also to that of other parts of
China, with its investment in light industry, and textiles,
metallurgical, automotive, and building materials industries in
other parts of the country amounting to five billion yuan, and
total output value of those industries topping 15 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Those enterprises that invest in Shanghai have also
benefitted. Statistics indicate that they have generated 30
billion yuan in business and paid nearly 400 million yuan in taxes.
</P>
<P>
Two of the more powerful participants in Shanghai's phenomenal
business atmosphere are Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces, whose
co-operative projects number more than 8,000 in Jiangsu. Zhejiang
has co-operated with Shanghai in 3,000 projects and sent 200,000
people to work in construction in the city. 
</P>
