<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jaruzelski Not To Be Tried Over 1981 Martial Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Poland's parliament today
decided that General Wojciech Jaruzelski and other former
communist leaders will not stand trial for their declaration of
martial law in the country in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The 460-seat lower house, or Sejm, voted 211-146 with 60
abstentions to free Jaruzelski from standing trial before the
State Tribunal, a special court for top officials, for
implementing military rule on December 13, 1981.
</P>
<P>
In separate votes, the deputies also let several other martial
law leaders off the hook.
</P>
<P>
Jaruzelski, 73, said he was satisfied with the vote and
repeated his views that martial law had been necessary to avert
the threat of a Soviet invasion and to end the economic crisis
crippling Poland at the time.
</P>
<P>
A special parliamentary committee agreed with Jaruzelski's
reasoning during a debate two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Jaruzelski, who ruled Poland from 1981 to the fall of the
communist regime in 1989, said that even today he deeply regretted
the various wrongs, sufferings and indignities that many people
experienced.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, martial law was "a lesser evil than the
threatening _ internal and external _ catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
During the one and a half years of martial law which started
in 1981, reports say that dozens of opposition activists were
killed and thousands jailed.
</P>
<P>
The case against Jaruzelski was opened five years ago when groups
which had struggled to overthrow communism were still in power.
</P>
<P>
They reached no conclusion because subsequent parliaments were
dissolved ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the ruling coalition of ex-communists and the Peasant
party won the general election which further delayed the debate.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Lech Walesa lost his re-election bid for the
presidency and former communist Aleksander Kwasniewski took over.
</P>
<P>
Jaruzelski still faces trial for the shooting by security
forces in 1970 of dozens of demonstrators protesting food price
rises. He was defense minister at the time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
