<HEADLINE> Clinton Declares State of Emergency in Southern California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
declared today a state of emergency in Southern California as
wildfires struck a three-county area this week, destroying more
than 100 houses and burning 37,000 acres (15,000 hectares).
</P>
<P>
Clinton ordered his top emergency management official, James
Lee Witt, to tour the disaster sites and also made available
federal funds for disaster housing, debris removal and emergency
protective measures the countries of Los Angeles, Orange and San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
"Due to the devastating effects of the Southern California
fires, I am declaring that a major emergency exists in the state
of California. As a result, federal funds will begin to flow
immediately to the people and communities of California affected
by this tragedy," Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
He also said that federal firefighters have joined with state
and local forces to form a human firewall from Malibu to the
Mexican border to extinguish the flames.
</P>
<P>
Airplanes and helicopters were battling the fires for a third
day Wednesday. The seasonal winds that drove the flames reaching
110 kph on Monday, were down to 40 kph today that helped the
fighting on the ground and in the air.
</P>
<P>
Firefighters tried to fasten their work as forecasters
predicted new winds from a cold front as early as Thursday
afternoon. 
