<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Top Navy Officials Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's three top Navy officials
resigned today as they opposed President Leonid Kuchma's soft
policy on the division of the former Soviet Union's Black Sea
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Aleksandr Kuzmuk signed a document accepting
the resignation of Navy Commander Vladimir Beskorovainy, Deputy
Commander Nikolai Kostrov and Chief of General Staff of Navy
Aleksei Ryzhenko, who were reported to be going to other posts
soon.
</P>
<P>
Beskorovainy, who attended the Ukraine-Russia negotiations on
the fleet division here between October 22-23, was accused of
"power abuse," the Ukrainian news agency UNIAN reported.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations were mainly focused on the division of the
former Soviet Union's Black Sea Fleet, the status and conditions
for the stationing of the Russian Black Sea Fleet in Ukraine as
well as accounts settlement for the leasing of Ukraine's Crimean
port of Sevastopol, said Vladimir Gorbulin, Secretary of the
National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As the navy commander who directly participated in the
negotiations, Beskorovainy should be held mainly responsible for
the fact that most of the ships Ukraine has got in the fleet split
with Russia needed to be repaired, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement reached between Russia and Ukraine
in April 1994, Ukraine got more than 20 ships in the first phase
in March this year and 54 ships in the second phase in August, and
the country is expected to gain some 164 out of the more than 830
ships of the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine and Russia have reached broad accords on dividing the
Black Sea Fleet but with no decision on the share-out of bases and
the future of its headquarters at Sevastopol, since the
disintegration of the former Soviet Union in 1991, a western news
agency report said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Mikhail Ezhely, an supervisor of the
Defense Ministry, will be appointed as Ukraine's Navy Commander.
</P>
