<HEADLINE> S'pore Gov't to Revise Downwards Growth Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore government is
to revise downwards its economic growth forecast for this year in
the wake of the worse-than-expected export performance in
September and expectations of a weak fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
According to a Straits Times report today, Trade and Industry
Minister Yeo Cheow Tong said the full figures for the third
quarter would be ready in a couple of weeks and the full year's
economic growth projection would then be adjusted.
</P>
<P>
"I think the fourth quarter will be fairly weak," he said to
local media after presenting this year's National Training Awards
Wednesday. "To what extent, we will only know in the next two
weeks or so", he added.
</P>
<P>
This will be the third time the government revises its Gross
Domestic Product forecast for this year.
</P>
<P>
The government had initially projected a seven to eight percent
growth for 1996. Then it increased the figure by half a percentage
point in May, after the first quarter's robust 10.9 percent
growth. However, the forecast was pared down to between seven and
eight percent in August, because of a slowdown in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Yeo said that when the government adjusted this year's growth
forecast to between seven and eight percent in August, it had
assumed that the second half of the year would turn in a similar
performance. Growth in the second quarter actually moderated to
seven percent.
</P>
<P>
He said a further slump in economic growth was likely in the
third quarter, since non-oil domestic exports for the third
quarter had dropped 2.4 percent. The exports figure is a key
indicator of the state of the manufacturing sector of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The drop in trade figures was due mainly to the slump in the
electronics sector, which had spillover effects on supporting
industries, such as the transportation and finance sectors, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
