<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAO: Hunger Strikes One in Every Five in Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 24 (Xinhua) -- While food insecurity is evident
in developed countries and widespread in parts of the former
Soviet Union, hunger afflicts about one in every five people in
developing countries, a top international food agency said today.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 841 million people, or 20 percent of the
developing countries' population, are hungry, the United Nations'
Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) said in a report prepared
for the World Food Summit scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
This figure, the Rome-based U.N. specialized agency noted, does
not include the hungry people in the industrialized countries or
in the countries with economies under transition.
</P>
<P>
South Asia, particularly India and Bangladesh, and Sub-Sahara
area were cited by the report as regions with the largest
proportion of undernourished people.
</P>
<P>
Sub-Sahara area is the only major area where the proportion of
undernourished people has risen over the last quarter century from
38 percent in 1969-1971 to 43 percent in 1990-1992, and famine is
still a threat, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the late 1960s, early 1970s or even the 1980s,
the symptoms of famine are evident today only in a few African
countries and localized in war zones, it said.
</P>
<P>
FAO blamed political, economic and environmental shocks and
inadequate preparedness within these countries for the continued
existence of the risk of famine.
</P>
<P>
In developed countries of North America and Europe, economic
problems that began in the 1980s and the more uneven distribution
of income in the past two decades, together with rising
unemployment, are responsible for the growing need for food
assistance, the organization said in the report.
</P>
<P>
In the Russian Federation and particularly in central Asia,
"malfunctioning markets, lack of safety nets, and underemployment"
were behind what the FAO report called "a substantial increase in
the food-insecure population groups" after the breakup of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The document called on policy-makers to recognize poverty as a
major cause of food insecurity and to include appropriate
macro-economic policies and development strategies as
preconditions for tackling nutritional problems.
</P>
<P>
Entitled "Food Security and Nutrition," and to be submitted to
the World Food Summit to be held November 13-17, the document also
urged the creation of an international reporting system for
measuring national progress toward nutritional well-being.
</P>
<P>
At the forthcoming meeting, leaders of nearly 200 countries are
expected to discuss ways to achieve universal food security and
agree on a Plan of Action to incorporate efforts by international
and non-governmental organizations, the private sector and civil
society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico to Enforce Law Against Helms-Burton Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's Foreign Ministry
announced today that the "Antidote Law" adopted to counter the
Helms-Burton Act will become effective Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The law, approved on October 1 by the Chamber of Deputies,
stipulates that economic sanctions will be imposed on any Mexican
or Mexican company that obeys any foreign resolutions that
prejudice commerce and investment.
</P>
<P>
Mexico believes that the Helms-Burton Act enacted by the United
States in March, in an attempt to drive foreign investors away
from Cuba, "is extraterritorial and violates international law."
</P>
<P>
Under the antidote law, any one who disobeys will be fined up
to 3,000 U.S. dollars. The Mexican Chamber of Deputies adopted
the law with 317 votes for and one against.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry and the Commerce and Industrial Promotion
Ministry will provide counsel to anybody who finds him/herself
affected by an extraterritorial law.
</P>
<P>
The antidote law would ban Mexican companies from answering
U.S. government questions about their Cuba operations, and would
guarantee help from the Mexican government if any lawsuits are
filed under the act. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Seeks Perot's Endorsement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- With less than two weeks to
go before the U.S. presidential election, Republican presidential
candidate Bob Dole's aides have asked the Reform Party's nominee
Ross Perot to quit the race and endorse him.
</P>
<P>
But, according to a report on CNN (Cable News Network)
television, his request was rejected by the Perot camp.
</P>
<P>
CNN said that Dole campaign manager Scott Reed made the urgent
entreaty at a meeting with Perot in Dallas. Republicans believe
that Perot has drawn support away from their party especially in
Florida, Texas, California and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
However, Perot spokeswoman Sharon Holman said, "Mr. Perot has
no intention of quitting the race, no intention whatsoever."
</P>
<P>
Dole made the plea 12 days before the election as Democratic
Party candidate, President Bill Clinton, was well ahead in
national polls and enjoying a similarly lopsided advantage in
state-by-state electoral vote counts.
</P>
<P>
A new NBC-Wall Street Journal poll, for example, had Clinton at
52 percent, Dole at 35 percent and Perot at 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dole advisers hoped a Perot endorsement could swing several
states in Dole's favor, especially in the Mountain West. Texas
and Florida are also two traditionally Republican states where
Clinton and Dole are running neck-and-neck.
</P>
<P>
Dole's camp expected to get Perot's endorsement because he
faces the prospect of getting less than 10 percent of the vote. He
gained 19 percent of the vote in the 1992 elections.
</P>
<P>
Republicans believe that most of Perot's support in Florida,
Texas, California and Ohio came from voters who would otherwise
vote Republican. 
</P>
</TEXT>
