<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries in the past few
days:
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil's coffee harvest for 1997-98 will be 24
million sacks (one sack weighs 60 kilograms), 2 million less than
the projected 26 million sacks for the 1996-97 harvest, the
Brazilian Rural Society predicted.
</P>
<P>
The 1997-98 coffee crop will not be able to satisfy the
internal and external demands for Brazilian coffee, which are
estimated at 29 million sacks, and is likely to lead to a serious
shortage unless a production of 30 million sacks were achieved in
the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Rural Society attributed the declining harvest in
the past few years to drought and frost in coffee-growing areas
and the low prices on domestic and foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Venezuela's foreign reserves have risen to 13.626
billion U.S. dollars, according to the latest bulletin of weekly
indicators announced by Venezuela's Central Bank. The bulletin
shows the reserves had major gains in the past few months thanks
to higher revenues from petroleum export and the inflow of foreign
capitals.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Milk production is expected to rise 7.2 percent
this year over last year, the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries
and Food predicted.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the drought that hit the country in the first half
of this year, Argentina's milk output will increase from 8.3
million tons last year to 8.9 million tons this year, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- Costa Rica's production of white corn could
increase from 25,000 tons last season to 50,000 tons this farming
season, which includes the last few months of 1996 and the first
few months of 1997, officials of the Agricultural Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The increased output could satisfy the domestic demand for next
year, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the huge rise to new technologies that
helped to promote the yield of corn in this Central American
country to five tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico will invest 1 billion U.S. dollars in the
mining industry between 1998-99, according to the National Mining
Chamber.
</P>
<P>
The organization said that favorable performance on
international markets had prepared conditions for making the
investments to maintain the country's privileged position in the
export of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Inter-American Development Bank will grant
Panama 70 million U.S. dollars in 1997 for three low-cost housing
programs, announced Deputy Housing Minister Rogelio Paredes Robles.
</P>
<P>
The programs include a joint financing program, a housing
program based on subsidies and savings and a program of quick
assistance for public housing. They will benefit people whose
monthly household incomes don not exceed 700 dollars.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's investments abroad reached 3.017 billion
U.S. dollars in the first nine months of this year, increasing 6
percent over the same period in 1995, Santiago's chamber of
commerce said. According to the chamber, 1.108 billion dollars
were invested during the Autumn quarter. Chile's investments
overseas since 1990 totaled 11.515 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Central Bank Lowers Discount Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Italy's central bank is to cut its
key discount rate on Thursday by 0.75 percentage points to 7.5
percent, taking it to the lowest rate since May 1994's 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The last rate cut was in July when the Banca D'Italia lowered
it from 9 percent to 8.25 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the cut was made possible by slower growth in the
annual rate of inflation which, for the first time since 1969, is
down to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
After the announcement, the foreign exchange and stock markets
fell slightly with a small devaluation of lira against the
U.S. dollar and the Deutsche mark.
</P>
<P>
The government said the move, which was welcomed by business
circles, is an important step towards Italy joining the single
European currency.
</P>
<P>
Italy wants to be one of the founders of European Monetary
Union, a unified monetary system of the European Union which will
involve the setting up of a single European currency in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
