<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Government Adopts Hospital Reform Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Austria's ministerial council
today adopted a bill on controversial hospital reform designed to
reduce government medical expenses.
</P>
<P>
The reform, described by Prime Minister Franz Vranitzky as a
"vital and right step" to protect the labor force, concerns a
hospital law and plans on hospital set-up and supply of medical
equipment.
</P>
<P>
The bill has to be passed by parliament before it comes into
effect.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, the doctor's working time, some as long as 100
hours a week now, will be shortened. In turn expenses will be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
It also allows small hospitals nationwide to keep one
specialized doctor on shift over weekends and at night, with
others staying at home ready for emergency calls.
</P>
<P>
The reform was favored by most medical personnel and hospitals
but opposed by the Doctors' Association, which said it would hurt
the hospital's medical quality.
</P>
<P>
The government said it will continue to negotiate with the
association and asked departments in charge of health in various
states to ensure that medical quality is guaranteed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GM Workers Accept Deal, Back on Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Workers at General Motors (GM)
Canada voted in favor of a new deal today, ending the 21-day
strike that paralyzed assembly lines and parts plants in North
America.
</P>
<P>
The workers are expected to go back to work as early as
tonight, the local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 20,000 GM workers in the United States and Mexico will
also return to work once Canadian plants start shipping parts.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Auto Workers (CAW) Union and General Motors Canada
reached a tentative deal Tuesday for a new three-year contract
after five days of intensive bargaining.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, GM's 26,000 workers got a two-percent wage
increase in each year of the three-year deal. With cost of living
protection, it could amount to a 10-percent wage increase.
</P>
<P>
GM Canada won the right to sell two parts plants, affecting
3,500 workers. However, the workers will have wages and benefits
protected under any new owner for three years.
</P>
<P>
As to the contentious outsourcing issue, the CAW-GM deal
largely followed a pact signed early with Chrysler Canada, in
which the company agreed on limits of outsourcing. GM reversed
its decision to outsource some 800 union jobs.
</P>
<P>
"I'm absolutely elated at the outcome of these negotiations,"
said CAW president Buzz Hargrove.
</P>
<P>
"Everybody won. The Canadian economy wins. General Motors
wins. The employees wins. The customer wins," noted GM's chief
negotiator Dean Munger.
</P>
<P>
The union will next turn to Ford Canada, the last of the Big
Three automakers, to bargain for a new contract. Talks are to
begin on October 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
