<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Warns of Looming Food Crisis in Eastern Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Intensified armed fighting and the
worsening security situation in eastern Zaire could lead to a
major hunger crisis affecting over 1 million Rwandan and Burundian
refugees, the World Food Program (WFP) warned today.
</P>
<P>
"Our window of opportunity (to avoid the crisis) is quickly
diminishing as events spiral out of control," said Trevor Rowe,
spokesman of the United Nations agency, which has been unable to
deliver humanitarian supplies to the region since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The worsening conditions in eastern Zaire has led to a cut-off
in humanitarian supplies, Rowe said. And "unless supply lines to
the refugee camps are opened immediately, the humanitarian
consequences in coming weeks could be devastating."
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to the international community to exert maximum
pressure to ensure the free movement of humanitarian relief," said
WFP, the largest international food agency based in Rome.
</P>
<P>
WFP has the capability to deliver food stocks from neighboring
Uganda and Tanzania for the refugees in eastern Zaire for the next
two months.
</P>
<P>
However, 75 WFP trucks with more than 2,200 metric tons of food
destined for Goma and Bukavu have been halted by Zairian
authorities since the weekend at the Zairian-Ugandan border for
security reasons.
</P>
<P>
In Goma, WFP has 7,200 tons of food in stock. But while these
supplies are enough to feed 727,000 people for three weeks,
delivery has been blocked by continued fighting in the north where
an estimated 500,000 refugees are camped.
</P>
<P>
To the west of Goma, where there are some 220,000 refugees,
there are no food stocks.
</P>
<P>
In Bukavu, WFP has already distributed food supplies to the
refugees which will last until the end of the month. The Program
now has only enough additional food stocks to feed the 300,000
refugees for an extra week.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Zaire has been set to explode in ethnic violence since
genocide and civil war in Rwanda in 1994 sent more than a million
Hutu refugees streaming in, stoking local rivalries.
</P>
<P>
But fighting has widened in the last six weeks since Zairian
troops reportedly joined ethnic clashes between native Zairians
and Tutsis, who have lived in Zaire for generations and are known
as Banyamulenge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
