<HEADLINE> Two killed in Argentine Boeing Jet Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Buenos Aires, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Two crew members were
killed and another six injured when an Argentine air force Boeing
707 broke up and caught fire during an emergency landing at Buenos
Aires International Airport Wednesday, officials reported.
</P>
<P>
The military cargo jet, which had left a military base in
Santiago, Chile, earlier in the day, had asked for an emergency
landing after reporting technical difficulties, airport
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the craft was attempting to land on one of the
runways when it suddenly dropped and hit the ground at about 2:30
p.m. local time (1730 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The jet then broke up and caught fire, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The eight crew members, who were thrown from the front section
of the plane, were all alive when rescuers found them.
</P>
<P>
Six were taken to hospital in the Buenos Aires suburb of Ezeiza
with serious burns, but one died shortly after arrival. Another
crew member was pronounced dead on arrival.
</P>
<P>
"Three of the injured are in a serious condition, while two
others are conscious but have severe injuries such as fractures
and abdominal injuries," said Carlos Sisko, a doctor at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
The crash was the second Boeing 707 accident in a day. In
Ecuador, a U.S. Boeing 707 cargo plane crashed into
densely-populated houses in the port of Manta on Tuesday night,
killing the three crew members and at least 27 people on the
ground and injuring as many as 80. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
