<HEADLINE> Philippine Opposition Parties Eye Merger for Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of two opposition
parties in the Philippines have started merger talks that will
lead to the fielding of a single ticket in the 1998 presidential
elections, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the Laban Ng Demokratikong Pilipino (Laban),
the biggest opposition party in the country, had agreed to merge
with the Nationalist People's Coalition (NPC) to boost the
opposition's chances of getting the presidency in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Laban and NPC leaders also reportedly hope to bring in the
Liberal Party, the People's Reform Party and other opposition
parties into a single opposition umbrella in preparations for the
elections one year and eight months away.
</P>
<P>
Senator Ernesto Herrera of the Laban said the Laban and the NPC
would create a joint committee in three weeks to thresh out
details of the proposed merger, including leadership of the new
party and rules on the selection of the common presidential ticket
for the 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
The Laban and the NPC had already been in alliance in the
senate and the House of Representatives. In October last year,
leaders of the two parties joined hands in ousting Senate
President Neptali Gonzales and installing NPC Secretary General
Ernesto Maceda instead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
