<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chamorro Urges People to Accept Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan President Violeta
Barrios de Chamorro today urged Nicaraguans to accept the results
of Sunday's general elections and remain calm.
</P>
<P>
"I am asking you to maintain calm and civility as we await the
final results, which will be announced by the Supreme Electoral
Council (CSE) as soon as possible," said the president in a radio
address to the nation this morning.
</P>
<P>
"We should accept the results of this election which has united
us all around this great civic celebration that we have just
completed," she said.
</P>
<P>
Chamorro also praised the civic spirit of the people during the
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
"We must all have confidence in the election results," she
added.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguans cast their ballots Sunday to choose a president, a
national assembly, town councils and the representatives to the
Central American Parliament. The election was carried out
peacefully without incidents.
</P>
<P>
With 73.2 percent of ballots counted, preliminary results
showed Arnoldo Aleman, the Liberal Alliance presidential candidate
and a former Managua mayor, won 48.85 percent of the votes and
maintained a 10.21 percent advantage over Daniel Ortega, of the
Sandinista National Liberation Front (FSLN).
</P>
<P>
Under Nicaragua's electoral law, the candidate who receives
more than 45 percent of the votes can be declared the winner but a
second round of voting must be held if none of the candidates
passed the 45 percent mark.
</P>
<P>
The final results are expected Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Aleman and Ortega, the candidates of the two major political
forces in the country, have pledged to respect and accept the
decisions of the CSE once it has completed its revision and the
counting of the votes according to the electoral law, Chamorro
said.
</P>
<P>
The Nicaraguan president will hand over the reins of power to
the winner of the elections on January 10, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the FSLN has denounced a series of "serious
irregularities" in the vote and demanded a full-scale revision of
the results.
</P>
<P>
Ortega, the former president, alleged Monday that telegrams
used to report provincial results to the CSE were "altered" and
did not reflect the number of votes his party obtained.
</P>
<P>
Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, one of the international
observers monitoring the elections, said the CSE had promised to
provide copies of the telegrams to those political parties to
enable them to double-check the results. International observers
described the elections as "fair." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
