<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Solves Problems of Wears and Food, White Paper (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Information Office of the
State Council issued a white paper here today saying that over the
past four decades, China's significant achievements in developing
grain production have not only basically eradicated the problem of
people not having enough to eat and wear and gradually raised the
living standards of the Chinese people, but also made great
contributions to the worldwide efforts to eliminate starvation and
poverty.
</P>
<P>
The "White Paper: the Grain Issue in China" published by the
Information Office of the State Council says that the
semi-colonial and semi-feudal old China before Liberation in 1949
was perennially haunted by the specter of starvation. For long
periods of time in the old days 80 percent of the population
suffered from starvation or semi-starvation because of the extreme
backwardness of agricultural production. Natural disasters nearly
always resulted in widespread deaths from starvation. In 1949
when the People's Republic of China was founded, the national
grain yield per hectare was only 1,035 kg, and the per capita
share of grain was only 210 kg a year.
</P>
<P>
After the founding of the People's Republic, the feudal
ownership of land was abolished. Under the leadership of their
government, the Chinese people devoted themselves to developing
grain production through self-reliance and hard work. As a result,
China is now able to feed 22 percent of the world's population on
about seven percent of the world's cultivated land. Total grain
output in 1995 increased by more than three times over that of
1949, or an annual average increase of 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
At present, China ranks first in total grain output in the
world, with the per capita share of grain reaching approximately
380 kg (including legume and tuber crops), which is the global
average. The per capita output of meat, aquatic products, eggs,
fruits and vegetables has reached 41 kg, 21 kg, 14 kg, 35 kg and
198 kg, respectively, which are all higher than the world's
average. Statistics from the UN Food and Agriculture Organization
show that China contributed 31 percent to the world's increased
grain output in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The white paper roughly divides the development of grain
production since the founding of New China into three phases:
</P>
<P>
The first phase (1950-1978): China's total grain output
increased from 113.2 million tons in 1949 to 304.8 million tons in
1978, an average annual growth of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The second phase (1979-1984): In 1984 China's total grain
output rose to 407.3 million tons, increasing by an average of 4.9
percent a year during the six years from 1979 to 1984. This second
phase saw the highest increase rate in the country's grain
production.
</P>
<P>
The third phase (1985-1995): In 1995 the country's grain
output totaled 466.6 million tons, increasing by an average of 1.2
percent a year during 11 years. Despite a lowered increase rate of
grain production, the quality of people's life was greatly
improved because of increased non-grain food supply during this
period, with the output of meat (pork, beef and mutton), aquatic
products, eggs, milk and fruit increasing by 1.8, 3.1, 2.9, 1.6
and 3.3 times over the figures of 1984.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says that the tasks ahead for the Chinese
government are, while ensuring a continued increase in grain
output, to vigorously promote diversified food production,
readjust the food structure, and continue to improve the people's
quality of life from the stage of simply having enough food and
clothing to leading a relatively well-off and comfortable life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0311 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Need 640 Million Tons of Grain by 2030, White Paper (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has, in
its report published today, predicted that China's grain
consumption will reach 500 million tons by 2000 and about 640
million tons by 2030.
</P>
<P>
The "White Paper: Grain Issue in China", published by the
Information Office of the State Council, predicts that by 2000 the
population will reach 1.3 billion and the total demand for grain
will be 500 million tons, based on 385 kg per person; by 2010 the
population will approach 1.4 billion and the total demand for
grain will be 550 million tons, based on 390 kg per person; and by
2030 the population will peak at 1.6 billion and the total demand
for grain will be approximately 640 million tons, based on 400 kg
per person.
</P>
<P>
The figures have been estimated in the light of the above trend
of change in consumption pattern and the estimated population
growth.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says that in the years to come a scientific and
moderate food consumption pattern which keeps pace with the
national economic growth and conforms to the situation of the
nation's agricultural resources should be brought into being among
both the urban and rural residents. The Chinese government will
strive to avoid a rapid increase in grain demand beyond the supply
capacity through guided grain consumption and tapping the
grain-producing potential as well as the potential of non-grain
food production.
</P>
<P>
The white paper says that since 1984, though the per capita
share of grain has been relatively stable, the nutritional status
of the Chinese people has markedly improved because of the
increased supply of food of animal origin. Food supply per person
per day in terms of calories reaches 2,727 kilocalories, including
those from 70 grams of protein and 52 grams of fat. This figure is
higher than the figures for those other countries with per capita
GNP comparable to China's. Therefore, it can be said that the food
supply in China has basically reached the average world level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
