<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Juvenile Delinquency Looms Large </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Juvenile delinquency is
alarmingly on the rise in Germany and criminal offenders are
becoming younger and younger, the Allgemeiner Deutscher
Nachrichtendienst news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The number of criminals below the age of 14 increased by 14
percent in 1995 compared with the year before, the news agency
said.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of youth criminals in the east is higher than
in the west. Young offenders accounted for one fourth of the total
criminals in the west while it is one third in the east.
</P>
<P>
The authorities are especially concerned about the fact that
more children under 14 were involved in crimes. Last year, the
number of juvenile delinquency in the state of Sachsen went up by
25 percent over 1994.
</P>
<P>
There was also a remarkable increase in violent crimes
committed by youngsters in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In Mecklenburg-Vopommern, more than half of the violent crimes
were committed by young people. In certain cities of the state,
the proportion was as high as 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
Sociologists believe that the rapid increase in juvenile
delinquency is due to the fact that young people are losing hope
for the future as they are increasingly facing the pressure of
unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
