<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, Colombia Hope for More NAM Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Both Indonesia and Colombia
wish to see economic cooperation further increase among the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) member countries, Indonesian President
Soeharto said.
</P>
<P>
In a statement at a banquet in honor of Colombian President
Ernesto Samper Pizano and his wife Wednesday evening, Soeharto
said there was no conflict of interest between Indonesia, once the
NAM chairman, and Colombia, the current NAM chairman.
</P>
<P>
He told his guests, who arrived here earlier in the afternoon
for a two-day visit to Indonesia, that Colombia's position as NAM
chairman was a manifestation of Latin American countries' sense of
responsibility toward the struggle of the Non-Aligned Movement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, President Samper said his current visit to Indonesia
as the NAM chairman is of vital importance.
</P>
<P>
"The visit reaffirms that the principles set by the movement's
founders are still valid both in Jakarta and in Bogota, or in
other parts of the world," Samper said.
</P>
<P>
He added that NAM must continue maintaining its multilateral,
rather than unilateral, approaches, its solidarity rather than
intervention and its cooperation rather than confrontation.
</P>
</TEXT>
