<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 25th Anniversary of China's UN Seat Marked in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The 25th anniversary of
the restoration of China's lawful seat in the United Nations was
marked here in New York today, with the presence of the U.N.
Secretary-General who made a complimentary speech to an audience
of hundreds.
</P>
<P>
On October 25, 1971, the 26th session of the U.N. General
Assembly passed a historic resolution, which ousted Taiwan and
accepted the People's Republic of China as the legitimate member
of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Chinese, waiting outside the U.N. headquarters and
shouting for China's seating, also saw the country having resumed
its seat as one of the five permanent members of the Security
Council at the end of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Peolpe's Republic of China has played a
growingly important role in the United Nations, which was
confirmed by the U.N. Secretary-General Boutros Boutros-Ghali, who
said china has made "immense contributions" to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"China's presence in the United Nations has added substantially
to its credibility and relevance as a truly universal
organization," Ghali said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Ambassador Qin Huasun summarized China's functions and
contribution to the U.N. endeavor for peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Qin said that China adheres to the principles of respect for
national independence and sovereignty, peaceful settlement of
disputes and non-interference in others' internal affairs. It
upholds justice and strongly opposes hegemonism and power
politics.
</P>
<P>
China has endeavored to safeguard the interests of developing
countries and played a unique role in maintaining world peace and
in seeking a fair and reasonable settlement of regional conflicts,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ambassador also gave an account of China's role in
solution to disputes and conflicts of different regions in the
world, including the Iran-Iraq conflict, the question of Cambodia,
the Gulf crisis, and the Korean nuclear issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. secretary-general confirmed China's understanding of
the unique and difficult role of the United Nations, which, he
said, is demonstrated by its long record of involvement and
support for the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The celebration was also marked by a panel discussion on
China's role in the U.N., Sino-U.S. relations and the Taiwan
issue.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the cautiousness China shows in the
United Nations, the Chinese ambassador explained that China did
act very cautiously, because "we believe we have great
responsibility in dealing with international issues, which might
be very complicated and call for great patience."
</P>
<P>
"China was against using the Security Council to exert pressure
and in favor of patient dialogue and negotiations," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
Nsanze Terence, Permanent Representative of Burundi to the
U.N., said that cautiousness is not weakness, but a well-thought
attitude. Burundi was one of the 76 countries in favor of China's
restoration to the U.N. in 1971. Referring to Taiwan's attempt to
be presented in the U.N., Terence said there is no provision in
the U.N. Charter that allows one U.N. seat be shared by two
delegations.
</P>
<P>
China should have the equal opportunity to be presented at the
U.N. and the World Trade Organization, said Olara A. Otunnu,
President of International Peace Academy, who presided over
today's meeting.
</P>
<P>
Some speakers also urged China and the United States to
improve their bilateral relations with more exchange of views at
higher levels.
</P>
<P>
Today's event was organized by a number of non-governmental
organizations, including the Foundation for U.S-China Relations
Inc., the U.S.-China Friendship Association and the Association
for the Reunification of China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stocks Retreat Sharply on Weak Wall Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Leading European stock markets
all dived sharply and finished lower on Wednesday, depressed by a
weak Wall Street and a chief Bundesbank economist's comments on
German economy.
</P>
<P>
British share on the London market closed well down in thin
trading, but above session lows, in line with a depressed Wall
Street, with the FTSE 100 index finishing 28.8 points lower at
4,028.4, as investors took profits after the recent
record-breaking surge.
</P>
<P>
The market was also hit by news released by the Bundesbank's
chief economist Olmar Issing that he did not expect any more
German interest rates cuts.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that Britain's September retail sales figures
released today failed to impact the market.
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt market also closed lower in response to losses in
New York and Issing's comments, with the DAX-30 index losing 19.45
points at 2,699.53.
</P>
<P>
Soft German bond prices and the weaker dollar also weighed on
the market.
</P>
<P>
The Paris bourse drifted lower in line with other European
markets and finished the session 26.75 points down at 2,148.86.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 leading British shares closed 28.8 points
down at 4,028.4. The Frankfurt DAX-30 index ended 19.45 points
lower at 2,699.53. The Paris CAC-40 share index finished down
26.75 at 2,148.86.  
</P>
