<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Conservation Congress Concludes in Montreal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTREAL, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The world's largest meeting of
conservation experts since the Rio Earth Summit concluded here
today, with commitments to tackle more vigorously with the globe's
environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
The congress, the first-time effort by the World Conservation
Union (IUCN) to make its triennial general assembly more
accessible to a wider audience, attracted more than 3,200
conservation scientists and practitioners, politicians and
business leaders from some 130 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
More than 55 workshops and hundreds of informal meetings were
held to look at issues such as economics and the environment, the
role of business in conservation, the impacts of climate change on
ecosystems and environmental security.
</P>
<P>
"This is the most energizing, exciting and useful meeting ever
held" in IUCN's 48-year-old history, said IUCN's outgoing
president Jay Hair.
</P>
<P>
"This is a working congress," added IUCN's Director General
David Mcdowell. The congress "generated many new approaches for
putting the ideals of Rio into action on the ground."
</P>
<P>
"The most innovative ideas can be grouped under 4 Ps:
partnerships, people, politics and the private sector," he noted.
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing prior to the congress' end, IUCN announced
an agreement with UNESCO to cooperate on the designation of world
heritage sites as well as promote an alliance on environmental
education and awareness.
</P>
<P>
To better promote the world's conservation, a new Biodiversity
Information System involving nine of the world's leading
conservation networks will be set up, which would become world's
most comprehensive data bank on species and ecosystems, IUCN said.
</P>
<P>
IUCN also announced its cooperation with the United Nations
Environmental Program in establishing the most comprehensive
global environmental law information system as well as
coordinating actions on biodiversity and trade programs.
</P>
<P>
During the 11-day congress, IUCN also put emphasis on its
traditional role as the most authoritative global forum on the
status of the world's biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
In its 1996 Red List of Threatened Animals released before the
congress, IUCN warned that 25 percent of all mammals may now face
the threat of extinction.
</P>
<P>
"We were astonished to find that the reality was worse than we
had imagined," said IUCN's newly-elected president Yolanda
Kakabadse. "This is an indicator of the health of the world's
ecosystems, and consequently, of our own health," she noted.
</P>
<P>
The congress debated more than 120 resolutions, ranging from
global issues such as the World Trade Organization to protecting
local world heritage sites and action plans for particular
species.
</P>
<P>
These will provide the programmatic framework for the future
work of IUCN, which has emerged as the largest grouping of
conservation organizations in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0338 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Telecom Policy Forum Concludes in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Delegates from 128 countries
concluded here Wednesday a telecom policy forum with in-depth
exchange of views on how to implement a host of new satellite
systems which may provide seamless global communications with
pocket-sized terminals.
</P>
<P>
The three-day forum, the first such event organized by the
International Telecommunication Union (ITU), focused on the policy
and regulatory issues which need to be addressed in order to
facilitate the introduction of the new systems which are
collectively called Global Mobile Personal Communications by
Satellite (GMPCS).
</P>
<P>
Unlike the communications satellites currently in operation,
these new GMPCS systems, most of them are scheduled to come into
operation within the next five years, will make use of a group of
non- geostationary satellites moving around the Earth in low or
medium orbit, transferring signals to earth stations or between
each other.
</P>
<P>
They could offer users a way to make phone calls, send fax
and even transfer multimedia data from and to anywhere in the
world, including remote areas or parts of the world with poor
fixed line telecommunications infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
However, the global coverage which can be provided by such
systems also raises a number of complex issues in the areas of
national sovereignty, service and equipment licensing and
interconnection with other carriers.
</P>
<P>
Particular concern was raised by developing countries whose
populations still have very limited access to the traditional
fixed line telephone services.
</P>
<P>
Josefina Lichaugo, Undersecretary for Communications of
Department of Transportation and Communications of the
Philippines, told a press conference that developing countries
"are caught in a dilemma" by the introduction of new telecom
technologies.
</P>
<P>
On the one hand, she said, developing countries do not want to
be left behind in the rapid development of telecommunications. On
the other hand, the regulatory authorities in those countries are
not ready for such new and complex technologies as GMPCS.
</P>
<P>
"We're looking upon to ITU to ensure that the implementation of
GMPCS will narrow the ever-widen gap (between developed and
developing countries," Lichaugo said.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Parapak, Secretary-General of the Department of
Tourism, Posts and Telecommunications of Indonesia, who was
elected as chairman of the forum, also pointed out that many
concern was voiced by developing countries that they can not move
in GMPCS as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
"They still need time to study it, and introduce it to
policy-makers, and to the regulatory authorities in their
countries," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
In a set of non-binding opinions adopted by the forum for
further consideration by governments in formulating their
policies, the participants stressed the need for respect of the
sovereign right of each country to regulate its
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
They also invited policy makers and regulators, GMPCS operators
and service providers to work cooperatively within the ITU to
facilitate the early introduction of GMPCS, subject to the
application of the relevant provisions of the radio regulations
and the particular requirements of each government.
</P>
<P>
GMPCS system operators and service providers are also urged to
take steps to ensure that their access and utilization charges are
set at a level that would make this service as widely utilized as
possible including in rural and remote areas in developing
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19961024.0339 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges for Cease-fire in Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Wednesday asked its diplomats in Zaire and Rwanda to urge leaders
of the two countries to do everything possible to defuse current
political tension that has arisen because of fighting in eastern
Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Warren Christopher sent urgent instructions
to those ambassadors this week as hundreds of thousands of Hutu
refugees were fleeing the refugee camps in eastern Zaire to escape
the fighting between the army troops and ethnic Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
"We've asked our ambassadors in Kinshasa and in Kigali, the
American ambassador in both Zaire and Rwanda, to appeal to them to
do everything possible to defuse the current political tension,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said.
</P>
<P>
The United States directed its appeal in part to the government
of Zaire in Kinshasa in the hopes that it can control over the
various military forces that are involved in the fighting, Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
The hostilities have been intensifying since early September as
Zaire's government accused the Banyamulenge, ethnic Tutsis who
emigrated from Rwanda decades ago, of planning a revolution
against the government.
</P>
<P>
Zaire has also accused Rwanda and Burundi, which are headed by
Tutsis, of supplying weapons and other support to their ethnic
brethren there as a way to express their displeasure with
Kinshasa's refusal to shut refugee camp, where live approximately
1.1 million Rwandan refugees and 145,000 Burundian refugees, most
of whom are Tutus who fled their countries for fear of retribution
by Rwandan and Burundian Tutsis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
