<HEADLINE> British Police Smash Drug Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- British police said today they
had broken up an international drug ring that laundered millions
of pounds in profits through British financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
A year-long operation ended with Brussels police seizing 5
kilos of pure heroin worth around 2 million pounds (3.2 million
U.S. dollars) and the arrest of three men and a woman in London.
</P>
<P>
"What we believe we have smashed today is an international
heroin network," Reuters quoted Southeast Regional Crime Squad
spokesman Jackie Bennett as saying.
</P>
<P>
"This organization was laundering multi, multi-millions of
pounds through British financial institutions," Bennett said, but
declined to name any of the institutions involved.
</P>
<P>
The operation involved more than 60 officers in London and
liaison with law enforcement agencies around the world.
Intelligence was passed to authorities in Canada and South Africa,
leading to arrests and drug seizures, Bennett said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
