<HEADLINE> FIFA Stress Ticket Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVE, October 23 (Xinhua) -- One week after the Guatemala
stadium tragedy that left 79 people dead, FIFA sent letters on
Wednesday to all national football federations to stress that only
tickets corresponding to numbered seats could be sold.
</P>
<P>
On October 16, a World-Cup elimination match at the Mateo
Flores de Guatemala Stadium ended in disaster when fans were
crushed or asphixiated to death. It was said that there were
30,000 people over the capacity of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
FIFA also indicated that entry tickets should be printed in a
way that is difficult to forge and that the kick-off whistle
cannot be blown until order has been established in the stadium.
</P>
<P>
International football representatives will be meeting in
Barcelona on December 7 to decide whether to ask France to remove
their stadia barriers for the 1998 World Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
Barriers in Guatemala contributed to the high injury rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
